<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Stresses Security in Solving Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and the U.S. consider
the security aspect as a crucial part of any future solution to
the Cyprus issue, government spokesman Michails Papapetrou said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily briefing, Papapetrou said the security
issue was discussed when President Glafcos Clerides met visiting
U.S. State Department coordinator for Cyprus Thomas Weston
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou said the U.S. considers Cypriot government's
proposal for the demilitarization of the island particularly
significant.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that any settlement to the Cyprus issue must
provide for the withdrawal of all troops and wider security
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
"We reiterated our position that the issue of security and
guarantees should be dealt with within the framework of a wider
force of guarantors and not to be left to Greece and Turkey, in
view of past experiences," he said.
</P>
<P>
Greece, Turkey and Britain had been guarantors for Cyprus'
independence and sovereignty when the island gained independence
from British colonial rule in 1960.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had used it as a pretext to invade Cyprus and occupy the
northern third of the island in 1974, following a failed coup
seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the island has been divided into Turkish
Cypriot-controlled north and Greek Cypriot-dominated south.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the U.N. Security-General Kofi Annan on December
17, 1993, Clerides proposed to disband Cyprus' National Guard and
turn over all its arms and military equipment to the custody of
the U.N. Peace-keeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) if Turkey agrees
to withdraw Turkish troops in the north and the Turkish Cypriot
armed forces are also disbanded and hand over their equipment to
UNFICYP.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Cypriot government would cover the cost
of a numerically increased UNFICYP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
