<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BT Unveils New Wearable Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A computer system created by
researchers at British Telecommunications (BT), which can be worn
on the body, has been unveiled at a disability conference held in
London.
</P>
<P>
The system uses the latest Pentium III laptop-style computer
connected to a pair of glasses, through which the user can view an
image equivalent to a normal desktop screen.
</P>
<P>
The BT research team, which demonstrated its prototype to the
Rehabilitation International Assembly in London, said it could
benefit people with degenerative Alzheimer's disease or the
disabled by acting as a "walking mind".
</P>
<P>
"We have developed a body-worn computer system that can behave
as a remembrance aid, accessing and delivering information when
you most need it based on where you are and what you are doing,"
said Jerry Bowskill, senior research scientist at BT.
</P>
<P>
"For people with memory problems it can act as a little helper,
reminding them of where they are and what they are doing," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The researchers hoped to bring the new wearable computer system
to the consumer market within the next two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
