<HEADLINE> Death Toll in Athens Earthquake Rises to 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from Tuesday
afternoon's powerful earthquake in the Greek capital of Athens
rose to 17, including one child.
</P>
<P>
The strong earthquake registering 5.9 on the Richter scale
occurred around 3 p.m. local time and it had an epicenter in the
Mount Parnitha region, some 20 kilometers northeast of Athens.
</P>
<P>
Many people were injured and a lot of people trapped in the
rubble of about 30 buildings in northeast Athens, and areas worst
hit are Menidi, Metamorphosi, and Kiffisia.
</P>
<P>
Currently, emergency rescue squad personnel are busy releasing
trapped persons and more than 1,000 tents will be allocated to the
homeless in regions worst hit by the quake.
</P>
<P>
Seismologists warned that there could be more aftershocks in
the next 48 hour.
</P>
<P>
The Greek armed forces and health and technical services have
been on alert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
