<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Mir Space Station Into "Drifting" State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Mir space station was
put into "drifting" state Tuesday to conserve energy and retain
the working capacity of the scientific instrument aboard.
</P>
<P>
Upon orders from Mission Control near, the gyrodynes were
stopped at 17:30 local time (13:30 GMT). Inertia will cause the
station to rotate once every 40 seconds, Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
The station's motion control system will be shut down at about
01:15 local time Wednesday (21:15 GMT Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
The 27th mission left the station on August 28 after partially
shutting down some systems and others completely. Some may be
activated later.
</P>
<P>
Only the telemetric and temperature regulation systems and the
command radio line continue to operate.
</P>
<P>
The 120-ton Mir station is expected to remain in the "drifting"
position until April 2000. If Russia cannot secure funds for the
continuation of its operations, a final crew will visit Mir in
February-March to prepare it for descent into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
