<HEADLINE> Angola Calls for International Intervention in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Angola hopes that the
international community will intervene "as soon as possible" in
the turbulent situation in East Timor, taking all necessary
measures to avoid genocide, Angolan Vice Foreign Minister said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We consider that the United Nations should take urgent
measures, sending intervention forces as substitution for the
Indonesian troops," said Toco Serao in an interview with Angola's
official news agency Angop.
</P>
<P>
Serao said that Angola is struck with "consternation" at the
turbulent situation in East Timor, accusing the pro-integration
groups of provoking the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He added that the situation in East Timor, which is under
occupation by Indonesia, is similar to an "authentic massacre" and
inspires profound worry.
</P>
<P>
On the amnesty granted by Indonesian President B.J. Habibie of
the pro- independence leader Xanana Gusmao who has been in custody
for seven years, Serao said this move is "extremely important" for
maintaining stability in the region and for pacifying the soul of
the East Timorese.
</P>
<P>
According to official announcement of the result of a
referendum held on August 30 in East Timor, an original Portuguese
colony annexed by Indonesia in 1976, 78.5% of the voters prefer an
independent country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
