<HEADLINE> Clinton, Blair, Mandela in Live Internet Broadcast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and former South African
President Nelson Mandela will take part in a live internet
broadcast on Wednesday to launch a website aimed at combating
global poverty.
</P>
<P>
A British government spokesman said Blair would take part in
the launch of Netaid's website (www.netaid.org) via a videolink
from Downing Street, the Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
The site will broadcast live concerts next month to raise money
for the poor.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Mandela will also take part in the launch via
satellite from the United States and South Africa respectively,
Netaid said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"They are all going to be launching it. They will be talking to
each other via webcast," the Downing Street spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Netaid concerts, which are due to be broadcast on October 9
simultaneously at stadiums in London, Geneva and New York, will
feature stars including Robbie Williams, George Michael and Celine
Dion.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the United Nations Development Program and Cisco
Systems, the concerts will also be broadcast on radio and the BBC
and MTV television channels.
</P>
<P>
Up to 60 million visitors to the website every hour will be
able to see and hear the performances, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
