<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Businesses to Get "Last Chance" Warning over Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Action 2000, British
government's Y2K task force, Tuesday launched a "last chance"
guide for businesses that have yet to recognize the dangers of Y2K
as well as those who are still to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
The booklet, a step by step guide to focus businesses on the
areas critical to their survival, will be mailed to Britain's 1.3
million businesses employing one to 249 staff from September 13,
Action 2000 said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that over quarter of a million of the 1.3
million small-to-medium sized firms are still not ready for Y2K,
despite repeated warnings over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem, or so-called "Millennium Bug", is a computer
software problem which could result in systems not recognizing the
new date in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Action 2000's Chairman Don Cruickshank
described the millennium date change as "the final challenge of
the 20th century" for thousands of small businesses.
</P>
<P>
"Action 2000 has a responsibility to ensure that every company
in the UK is alerted to how to protect their business from risk of
disruption from the bug," said Cruickshank.
</P>
<P>
"This is why we have taken the unprecedented step of mailing
1.3 million named senior individuals from those companies
employing between one and 249 staff," he said.
</P>
<P>
With time rapidly running out, the guide, labelled as "final
lifeline", is designed to be a concise and easy to use tool for
businesses to assess risks, identify problems and take action to
beat the Bug.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
