BAGHDAD -- Iraq's Trade Ministry Tuesday accused the
U.S. representative at the U.N. Sanctions Committee of hindering
approval of its electrical contracts signed under the oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ministry told the Iraqi News Agency that
the blocked contracts with Spanish, French and German companies
involved equipments and spare parts for the electrical sector.
(BC-Iraq-UN-Contracts)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- The first batch of the Palestinian prisoners of 200
will be set free Thursday, Minister of Local Government in the
Palestinian National Authority Saeb Erekat said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming release comes under the revised agreement for the
Wye Accord, or the Sharm El-Sheikh memorandum, signed Sunday by
the Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under the new agreement, among other things, Israel will
release 350 political Palestinian prisoners in two phases. The
second batch of 150 will get freedom on October 8.
(BC-Palestine-Prisoners)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian police shot and killed four suspected Islamic
militants, including a wanted key member of a violent group, in
their hideout in Giza Governorate.
</P>
<P>
The four men, holed inside an apartment in el-Omraniya suburb,
showered police with bullets. The police, which was preparing to
storm into the apartment, fired back, killing all four men.
(BC-Egypt-Militants-Shootout) 
