<HEADLINE> U.S. Awaiting U.N. Report on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States would be
waiting for a report by a U.N. fact-finding team about East Timor
before deciding whether to send forces there, the White House said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. team will report back within the next couple of days
and make an assessment on any potential international peacekeeping
force, and we'll take a look at that recommendation," White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
"Once they've made a judgment on that... we will, as will many
countries, take a look at whether we participate," he added.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart told reporters that President Bill Clinton had not
made any offer of troops or equipment to support any U.N.-backed
intervention because U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan had not
decided himself whether an international force was warranted.
</P>
<P>
"The important thing now, as we've stressed, is the Indonesian
government getting control of the situation and restoring a secure
environment," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
He declined to say what the United States would do if the
Indonesian government failed to restore peace in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Washington has said its relations with Jakarta would be damaged
if the Indonesian government could not bring the turmoil in East
Timor under control.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon officials said there were no immediate plans for any
emergency rescue operation for U.S. nationals in East Timor. They
said three U.S. naval vessels were expected to sail from Port
Darwin, Australia, as early as Wednesday and could move toward the
troubled area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
