<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Popularizes Knowledge to Guard Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia is making efforts
to popularize knowledge to guard against the deadly Acquired
Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS).
</P>
<P>
Lessons on the causes and prevention of the spread of AIDS had
been given to about one million people in the western zone of the
Tigray State, Ethiopian News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The lessons were also given through AIDS clubs, schools, public
 conferences and churches, hygiene expert Kidane Wold-mariam was
quoted as sayCing.
</P>
<P>
He said discouraging promiscuous sexual practices and
eradicating harmful traditions such as non-clinical circumcision
and tattooing should be given due attention to preventing the
spread of the lethal disease.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, about 2.5 million people out
of a population of 60 million in Ethiopia have either developed
AIDS or carried HIV, the virus that leads to AIDS.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of the male population aged between 15 and 49
could die by 2009 because of the deadly disease, medical workers
warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
