<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Islamic Militants Killed in Shootout with Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian police shot and killed
four suspected Islamic militants, including a wanted key member of
a violent group, in their hideout in Giza Governorate.
</P>
<P>
The four men, holed inside an apartment in el-Omraniya suburb,
showered police with bullets. The police, which was preparing to
storm into the apartment, fired back, killing all four men.
</P>
<P>
Among the dead was Farid Salem Abdel Qadwani, identified by an
Interior Ministry official as a leader of al-Gamaa al-Islamiya, or
the Islamic Group, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Two of them were identified as Saad Nureddin Abdel Galil and
Kasban Sayed Mahfouz, the official said. The identification of the
fourth suspect was in progress.
</P>
<P>
The official said Qadwani and the other three carried out many
attacks on police patrols in southern Egypt in 1993 and 1994, the
height of the Islamic militant insurgency aimed at toppling
Egypt's secular government.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 people have been killed since the militants
took up arms in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Qadwani was twice sentenced to life in prison but had been at
large, police said without giving additional information.
</P>
<P>
The shootout was the first in months that police had with
suspected Islamic radicals.
</P>
<P>
The incident came a day after Hussein Mahmoud Sulaiman, a
40-year-old clothing vendor, described as an Islamic fanatic,
grazed President Hosni Mubarak's hand with a sharp tool in
northern Port Said at the northern end of the Suez Canal and was
shot dead by guards.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's government has launched a harsh crackdown on Islamic
fundamentalism in Egypt. In recent years, it declared the movement
crushed, with most of its leaders put in jail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
