<HEADLINE> Britain Rules Out Sanction on Indonesia Over Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Tuesday ruled out
using economic sanctions against Indonesia in an attempt to bring
an end to the escalating violence in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Office Minister John Battle said sanctions would have
little effect and more positive approach was needed to solving the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Battle made the comment in Indonesian capital Jakarta before
holding talks with Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas on the
crisis, a BBC report said.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment the economy of Indonesia is under incredible
pressure with the collapse of the economies in South East Asia so
that [sanctions] would not have any immediate effect," the report
quoted Battle as saying.
</P>
<P>
Calls for sanctions are growing in Britain amid reports that
Indonesia soldiers have joined pro-Jakarta militias in their
attacks on civilians.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, a group of East Timorese protested outside
Downing Street, British Prime Minister Tony Blair's residence.
They insisted that Britain has a moral obligation to help end the
bloodshed in their homeland.
</P>
<P>
The campaigners staged a vigil after handing in a letter
demanding that the British government uses its influence to get
Indonesia to allow United Nations peacekeepers into East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook cut short his
visit in Tokyo and flew to New Zealand to attend emergency talks
over the bloodshed in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Cook said Britain would be heavily involved in the crisis in
East Timor, saying Britain has "got a ship in the area which could
be of assistance if it was required."  
</P>
</TEXT>
