<HEADLINE> U.S. Optimistic about Algeria's National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. is optimistic about
Algeria's sincerity on national stability, U.S. Assistant
Secretary of State for Middle East Affairs Martin Indyck said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. supports the efforts of Algerian President
Abdelaziz Bouteflika in introducing the economic and political
reform. He also conveyed Washington's desire to strengthen ties
with Algeria.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 100,000 people have been killed since an Islamic
insurgency erupted in 1992 when the military-backed government
canceled elections that the now banned Islamic Salvation Front was
set to win.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official highlighted the importance of Algeria's role
on the regional and international arenas while voicing his
country's readiness to back the economic development in Algeria,
Morocco and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
On the African affairs, Indyck said Algeria's efforts to
resolve the Eritrean-Ethiopian border dispute and the crisis of
the Democratic Republic of Congo were widely hailed regionally and
internationally. "We encourage such endeavors," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the Middle East peace process, Indyck said the U.S. and
Algeria had common interest in achieving an Arab-Israeli fair,
lasting and comprehensive peace.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome Bouteflika's support and participation in the peace
efforts," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Algeria's efforts in enlarging "the peace circle" will have a
great importance due to the country's regional weight, according
to the U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
Indyck arrived here Monday on a two-day working visit and held
talks Monday night with Bouteflika. 
</P>
