<HEADLINE> Iraqi Parliament Slams U.S.-British Bombardment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi National Assembly
(parliament) has slammed the continuation of the U.S.-British
bombardment of Iraqi civilian targets as "heinous crime against
humanity."
</P>
<P>
In memos sent to the International Parliamentary Union and the
Arab Parliamentary Union, the Human Rights Committee at the Iraqi
National Assembly described the continuation of U.S.-British
bombardment as aggressive acts, the Iraqi News Agency reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the committee Khalid As-Saadi said in the memos
that the U.S.-British bombardment was basically aimed at harming
Iraqis and destroying their properties.
</P>
<P>
As-Saadi reviewed the details of the U.S.-British warplanes
attacks against Iraqi civilian targets, and the human and
material losses they inflicted on Iraqi civilians.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the attacks against residential areas,
service facilities and worship places in northern and southern
Iraq is a flagrant violation of human rights and international
norms and values.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration and British government are still
continuing their hostile acts by bombing civilian facilities and
residential areas and killing scores of innocent civilians
including children, women and the elderly, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's U.S.-British airstrikes against Iraq,
their warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian and
military targets in the no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
The restricted zones were imposed by the U.S.-led western
allies in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from possible attacks by Iraqi government troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
