<HEADLINE> EU to Provide 11.4 Million Euro Aid  to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 7 (Xinhua) -- An European Union official said
Tuesday that EU would provide 11.4 million euro to Zimbabwe early
next year for education programs to be implemented over a
four-year period.
</P>
<P>
EU economic adviser Jose Leandro told the Zimbabwe News Agency
that talks between the Zimbabwean education ministry and the EU
were in the final stages and expected to reach an agreement soon.
</P>
<P>
He said the money was going to be used to resolve both long
term and short term needs of the educational sector.
</P>
<P>
"On the short term needs, the money will be used to cover
financial difficulties of those children who were failing to
attend school because of exorbitant levies.
</P>
<P>
"On the long term the money would be used by the ministry to
monitor the impact of its policies," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "It is good that the International Monetary Fund has
agreed to release funds to Zimbabwe but despite that being one of
our condition our support does not flow automatically because we
still need to look at other issue."
</P>
<P>
"Our main concern is the government's commitment to the social
sector especially in the areas of education and health," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said they also wanted to see the government's commitment to
the privatization process and its military expenditure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
