<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8 Killed in Athens Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Eight people were killed,
dozens injured and many more trapped in an estimated 30 collapsed
buildings in the Greek capital of Athens when a powerful
earthquake measuring 5.9 on the Richter scale hit the city around
3 P.M. local time Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas described the damage as "significant", saying that
the Greek armed forces, and health and technical services were on
alert while rescue teams were on the scene to begin efforts to
release those trapped in the buildings in the city's northern
outskirts, especially in the area of Thracomakedones, Menidi, Nea
Ionia, Halkidona, Ano Liosia, Kato Fifissia and Nea Erythrea.
</P>
<P>
Two 400kv high voltage centers were also damaged by the
earthquake and the wider Athens region was now serviced by an
150kv center.
</P>
<P>
Helicopters are now flying over the above-mentioned areas to
detect and determine the extent of the damage.
</P>
<P>
So far, firemen have released three women and a nine-year-old
boy trapped in a building which had collapsed during the quake,
which had an epicenter in the Mount Parnitha region, some 20
kilometers northeast of Athens.
</P>
<P>
Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis chaired an emergency
meeting of ministers to coordinate the rescue actions.
</P>
<P>
After the strong earthquake around 3 P.M. local time, there
were also more than 20 aftershocks and the strongest of the
aftershocks registered 4.5 on the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
Quake experts warned that the next 48 hours could see
aftershocks of up to more than 4 Richter and possibly close to 5.0
Richter while saying that the earthquake was a surface movement
and it originated from a fissure 20 kilometers in length and no
more than 10 kilometers in depth.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake also sent thousands of frightened residents into
the streets while hospitals in the city area have evacuated their
patients. Traffic lights knocked out by the earthquake led to
traffic chaos in the city center and mobile phone network also
appeared to have been knocked out by the quake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
