<HEADLINE> Dutch Deputies To Pay Political Visit To Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch government said on
Tuesday that Foreign Trade Minister Gerrit Ybema will be paying a
visit to Cuba as the first political visit by the Netherlands to
the socialist island country since 1979.
</P>
<P>
This is a joint initiative on the part of the Netherlands
Foreign Trade Agency, the Institute for Latin America and the
Amsterdam Chamber of Commerce, the government said in a news
release.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch foreign trade minister will lead a delegation of
deputies from Dutch industry to pay this visit between October 28
and November 3. The visit is consistent with the Dutch policy of
stepping up the dialogue with Cuba wherever possible, the
Government Information Council said.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch government will further carry out the policy in order
to prevent the Netherlands from slipping behind other countries
and "to create a more solid foundation for vigorously exposing
socio-political wrongs," the news release said.
</P>
<P>
"Economically, the Netherlands has a strong position in Cuba,
particularly in the fields of trade and shipbuilding," it added.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 30 Dutch firms have their branches in Cuba. Now,
the Netherlands is the third-most important market after Russia
and Canada for the Cuban exports, which is about 455 million NLG
(218 million U.S. dollars) per year. Meanwhile, Cuban imports of
100 million NLG (48 million U.S. dollars) a year put the
Netherlands in 11th place, the statistics show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
