<HEADLINE> Judge Safety Causes Fear of Distraction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- More judges are worrying about
their safety in the face of threats of death, bombs and other
dangers arousing concerns about impartiality, the Globe and Mail
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More federally appointed judges are contacting the Office of
the Commissioner for Federal Judicial Affairs to seek extra
protection, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"We have had these calls that we had not had before," the
Ottawa office of the agency was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Among the anecdotical evidence is a case where a judge received
threats to his life and the lives of his family because of a
ruling he made in a criminal case involving organized crime,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Police took the threats seriously and had the judge change the
color of his car, while the Office of the Commissioner for Federal
Judicial Affairs provided a home alarm.
</P>
<P>
Madam Justice Myra Bielby of the Court of Queen's Bench of
Alberta told reporters that the concern among judges is not
affecting their judgments, but no one would be served well by
distracted judges, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
