<HEADLINE> Greek FM Expects Positive Initiatives on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Greek Alternate Foreign
Minister Yiannos Kranidiotis said Tuesday that there was potential
for a serious initiative concerning the solution of the thorny
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remark here after meeting the newly-
appointed special U.S. coordinator to the Cyprus problem, Thomas
Weston.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis told reporters that the Cyprus problem could not
remain "an open wound" because it undermined stability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that Washington, the U.N. and the EU would
pressure Turkey to cooperate with the international community for
a settlement of the problem.
</P>
<P>
Weston, who arrived here Tuesday from Cyprus, said that there
were positive elements at the international level for the solution
of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north since 1974, when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Weston is now on his first trip to the region as part of the U.
S. efforts to restart the deadlocked talks on reunifying the war-
divided island. 
</P>
