<HEADLINE> S. Africa Preparing 230 Troops for Congo Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is preparing
230 soldiers for possible participation in a United Nations
peacekeeping mission in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC), South African Defense Minister Patrick Lekota said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa's contribution to the mission would depend
solely on what was required by the U.N. and the Organization of
African Unity.
</P>
<P>
"Only when we are invited to contribute a contingent to build
the peacekeeping force can we do so. Therefore we can only know
how much we are going to participate when a request is presented
to us by the U.N."
</P>
<P>
The deployment of peacekeeping troops would form the third
phase of putting into effect a cease-fire agreement signed by all
warring factions in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The first phase involved the deployment of unarmed military
liaison officers to the capitals of all the signatories to the
peace accord, and possibly the headquarters of the rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has trained eight military officers for
involvement in the first stage, of which one was chosen.
</P>
<P>
Lekota said Colonel Hans Swart left for Kenya on Monday for
specific training. It was expected that he would be deployed in
Kampala, Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The military liaison officers would be responsible for
assisting the Joint Military Commission, comprising
representatives of all the parties to the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
They would also secure assurances of security from all the
parties prior to the possible deployment of military observers in
the DRC, which would form the second phase of the program.
</P>
<P>
South Africa had not yet been asked to take part in the second
or third phases, Lekota said.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Johan van der Walt, senior staff officer of operational
planning and external operations, said 72 volunteers were being
trained as UN military observers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
