<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF: Study Shows Effective Anti-Malaria Alternatives to DDT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Various innovative mechanisms
can control malaria and other diseases just as effectively as the
notoriously dangerous pesticide DDT, according to the World Wide
Fund for Nature (WWF).
</P>
<P>
These alternatives would be less harmful to the environment and
human health and just as cheap, said the WWF in a report released
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The results came from detailed case studies focused in six
areas: Africa, India, the Philippines, South America and Mexico.
The alternative techniques used include pesticide-impregnated
bednets, odor-baited cloth targets to attract and destroy
disease-carrying insects; lower-risk pesticides used in rotation
to avoid the development of resistance; and widespread elimination
of mosquito breeding grounds and introduction of natural predators
and sterile insects.
</P>
<P>
The WWF said that the results confirmed that 34 million people
in West Africa were protected from river blindness and 700,000
Indians from malaria. There was a 50 percent reduction of malaria
in certain Tanzanian villages, and a 50 percent reduction in
malaria cases in the Philippines with 40 percent less expenditure.
</P>
<P>
"If DDT were the only tool to fight malaria, we would not even
consider advocating its phase-out," said Clifton Curtis, Director
of WWF's Global Toxics Initiative. "However, as these case studies
show, people around the world are using innovative methods to
fight tropical diseases that do not rely on a pesticide so
dangerous it has been banned in most countries." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Locate New Gene for Dyslexia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Scientists said Tuesday they
have identified the location of a gene for dyslexia, raising the
hope of screening tests and early treatment for this common
learning disorder.
</P>
<P>
The DYX3 gene, discovered by an international team of
researchers based in Norway, Belgium, and the United States, lies
within a small region of chromosome 2, one of the 22 chromosomes
that everybody inherits from their parents.
</P>
<P>
The discovery, published in Britain's Journal of Medical
Genetics, strongly indicates that dyslexia manifests differently
among those who inherit the gene for it.
</P>
<P>
The researchers believed that they will now be able to clone
the genetic sequence and so gain important insights into the
processes involved in reading and spelling, for which it is
thought several genes may be responsible.
</P>
<P>
No gene for dyslexia has been isolated until now, although
scientists have long suspected a genetic basis for the disorder
and have even roughly mapped the region of the brain likely to be
involved.
</P>
<P>
Previous research indicated that many children under the age of
two, in whom the language areas of the left side of the brain are
impaired, can go on to develop normal language ability, unlike
teenagers and adults who sustain damage to this area.
</P>
<P>
"This suggests that the areas of the brain responsible for
language development are relatively plastic in the early years of
life," said the researchers.
</P>
<P>
"A genetic test that could detect dyslexia early in life could
therefore facilitate earlier diagnosis and corrective treatment,"
they concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
