<HEADLINE> Disarmament Conference Ends 1999 Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Conference on Disarmament
(CD) concluded its 1999 session here Tuesday without agreement on
a program of work, said the United Nations Office at Geveva.
</P>
<P>
While agreement had been reached on most of the elements of a
program, the UN said, major differences remained among national
delegations on two topics: nuclear disarmament and prevention of
an arms race in outer space.
</P>
<P>
However, the conference, the world's sole multilateral forum
for disarmament negotiations, have taken a consensus decision to
admit five new members, Ecuador, Ireland, Kazakhstan, Malaysia,
and Tunisia, increasing the total number of the CD members to 66.
</P>
<P>
In its press release at the conclusion of the CD's 1999
session, the United Nations recalled that on March 26, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin delivered a speech before the CD. Jiang was
the first head of state to speak before the conference.
</P>
<P>
The CD has fixed the following dates for its session for the
year 2000, which will take place in three parts: January 1 to
March 24, May 22 to July 7, and August 7 to September 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
