<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Cuts Likely to Ground Canada's Snowbirds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Snowbirds aerobatics team
of Canada is losing its 14 ageing Tutor aircraft as part of the
defense budget cuts, according to the Ottawa Citizen newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Citing a Jane's Defense Weekly report, the newspaper said
Tuesday that the air force has been trying to come up with 2
billion Canadian dollars (about 1.3 billion U.S. dollars) to
upgrade its frontline CF-18 fighter fleet and Aurora patrol
planes.
</P>
<P>
It is considered impractical to keep Tutors just for the sake
of Snowbirds, which perform at Canada Day celebrations every year,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The scaledown also involves other types of aircraft, the
newspaper reported, adding the Challengers will cease flying by
May 2000 and the Silver Stars will be withdrawn from service by
the end of March 2002.
</P>
<P>
In addition, two Dash-8 trainers based in Winnipeg are to go
out of service, while the search and rescue Buffalo aircraft will
be eliminated on the west coast.
</P>
<P>
In total, more than 50 support aircraft are expected to be
removed from the flight lines, reducing the air force to half the
size it was in 1991, the newspaper quoted defense analysts as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Assist Turkey in Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James
D. Wolfensohn Tuesday told Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
that the bank is intensifying its commitment to assist the
government in its reconstruction and recovery programs in the
aftermath of the August 17 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
"I am very pleased to convey that the World Bank is preparing a
1 billion dollar package for Turkey to help finance the costs of
reconstruction and recovery," Wolfensohn said. "This package will
take the form of 300 million dollars in re-allocations from
existing loans to Turkey and up to 750 million dollars in new
long-term loans, which would be committed over the next three
months."
</P>
<P>
Within 36 hours of the earthquake, the World Bank had
reallocated funds from existing loans and had identified funding
for new loans for reconstruction needs, the bank said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
As the full extent of the damage and needs for recovery have
become clearer, the bank has augmented the amounts to make even
more financial and technical resources available to support
Turkey, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"We are aware that the overall costs of reconstruction will be
much greater than those we can finance. Consequently, the bank is
working with other international agencies and countries that could
offer bilateral assistance, to ensure that remaining costs are
financed," Wolfensohn said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bank will assist and advise the Turkish
government as it works to improve the systems for enforcement of
building codes, insurance, and overall emergency response.
</P>
<P>
Two World Bank teams are now working with the government in
Turkey -- one is assessing the costs of reconstruction and service
restoration, and the other is assessing the impact of the
earthquake on the economy and the needs for economic recovery.
Both teams will make their first results available by September
14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
