<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America Promotes Tourism in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Latin American
visitors contributed 10 percent of foreign visitors to the United
States in 1998, said reports here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, the number of visitors from the region to the United
States, with the exception of Mexico, represented only 6.9 percent
of visitors, the newspaper Portafolio quoted experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
Including Mexicans, the visitors from Latin America and the
Caribbean represent 31 percent of the approximately 46.4 million
foreign visitors, who stayed at least one night in the United
States last year.
</P>
<P>
Canada contributed to the tune of 29 percent of the visitors,
Europe 22 percent, and Asia 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Between 1990 and 1998, the general growth in international
visitors to North American cities was approximately 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of visitors from Latin America and the Caribbean
shot up 42 percent to 14.1 million.
</P>
<P>
Visitors from South America rose 123 percent in 1998, those
from Central America grew 69 percent and those from the Caribbean
went up only 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mexicans who spent one night in the U.S. registered an increase
of 32 percent to 9.27 million, representing the highest number.
</P>
<P>
The increase was especially strong from Argentina, with a rise
of 183 percent, totaling 524,000 visitors last year, followed by
Brazil, with an increase of 128 percent, to 909,000.
</P>
<P>
Florida is the most popular destination in the United States,
attracting two thirds of Caribbean visitors, 70 percent of Central
American visitors and 61 percent of South Americans.
</P>
<P>
New York and California are also popular places with the Latin
Americans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
