<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Effort to Reduce World's Illiterates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan has called upon the United Nations and Member States to
work jointly to reduce illiterates in the world at large.
</P>
<P>
In a message for International Literacy Day, which falls on
September 8 every year, Annan said, "The United Nations and Member
States must work jointly to build societies, where literacy is
integrated into overall development efforts."
</P>
<P>
"We must aim to create competence and skills that enable people
to confront and solve problems, formulate their own vision of
development and make informed judgements in all decision-making
processes," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must optimize the use of technologies, both traditional and
new, to help bridge the knowledge gap," he said. "We must strive
to provide lifelong learning opportunities for all."
</P>
<P>
"That means working as a time," he said. "The United Nations
and UNESCO (the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization), the lead United Nations agency in
education, relies on cooperation with all United Nations Member
States. financial partners, civil society associations and the
hundreds of thousands of literacy workers -- most of them
volunteers -- around the world."
</P>
<P>
There are 880 million illiterates in the world today.
Two-thirds of them are women. More than 120 million children are
deprived of all education, formal or informal.
</P>
<P>
"Unless we step our commitment of literacy, they will be the
adult illiterates of tomorrow," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The latest UNESCO estimates give us cause for hope," he said,
"The percentage of adult illiterates in the world has already
declined from more than one-third in 1970 to a quarter in 1990."
</P>
<P>
"It is projected to drop below one-fifth in the beginning of
the new millennium," he said.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO decided in 1966 to designate September 8 ever year as
"the International Literacy Day," in a bid to mobilize all
governments and international organizations to wage a fight
against illiteracy in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
