<HEADLINE> Brazilian Businessmen Welcome New Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRAZILIA, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's private sector on
Tuesday welcomed the naming of Alcides Tapias as the new
Development, Industry and Trade Minister.
</P>
<P>
According to businessmen, the arrival of Tapias to the cabinet
of Brszil encourages the productive sector, as he was successful
as vice-president of the Bradesco Bank, one of the largest in
Brazil, and is also an ex-president of the Brazilian Federation of
Banking Associations.
</P>
<P>
The industrialists showed confidence in Tapias, believing that
he will develop financing systems for the exports of the small and
medium sized businesses of Brazil, as the country needs employment
and growth.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion of the businessmen, the fight against
protectionism in developed countries and the promotion of the
formation of large business groups, is a principal part of the
work of the new minister.
</P>
<P>
The 57-year Tapias was named by President Henrique Cardoso on
Monday, replacing Clovis Carvalho, who resigned last Friday,
because of a divergence in economic policies with Finance
Ministrer Pedro Milan.
</P>
<P>
Some local analysts see the departure of Carvalho as the latest
conflict within the government and its allies over whether to
pursue the tough fiscal cuts agreed to with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), despite a sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
Brazil has agreed with the IMF to reach strict fiscal targets
in exchange for a 41.5 billion dollar loan package aimed at
bailing Latin America's biggest economy out of the devastating
effects of its 30-plus currency devaluation in January.
</P>
<P>
the country is fighting sky-high unemployment, a stagnating
economy and high interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
