<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Unveils Health Plan In New Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
Tuesday unveiled a health program to bring millions of uninsured
Americans into the health care system and improve coverage for
those already in it.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic presidential candidate promised to offer
affordable heath care to the nation's nearly 11 million
uninsured children by 2005, marking a new campaign season of
specific policy prescriptions by presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
Gore made clear that, if elected president, he would pursue the
same incremental approach to changing managed care that President
Bill Clinton adopted after his attempt to revamp the system failed
to win congressional approval in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"We have all learned that we cannot overhaul the system in one
fell swoop," Gore said in a speech at Children's Hospital in Los
Angeles. "Experience has taught us that there is a way to keep
what is right, while fixing what is wrong with American health
care."
</P>
<P>
Gore's speech came one day before Democratic rival Bill Bradley
formally declares his candidacy in his hometown of Cristal City,
Missouri, and a few days after Republican front-runner George Bush
outlined his support for school vouchers in an address to the
Latino Business Expo in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
After a summer focused in large part on fund-raising prowess
and a nonbinding straw poll, leading candidates are now preparing
policy addresses on specific topics.
</P>
<P>
The Children's Health Fund, an advocacy group for disadvantaged
children, estimates some 11 million children have no health
insurance in the U.S. and almost as many have inadequate plans or
live in places without enough doctors.
</P>
<P>
To help insure more children, Gore would expand the Children's
Health Insurance Program, which helps states provide coverage to
children in working families.
</P>
<P>
Gore would also allow families that do not qualify for the
program, and do not receive health benefits through their jobs, to
buy into the program.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested to allow "vulnerable Americans" to buy into
the Medicare program as early as age 55 and he promised a 25
percent tax credit to help defray the cost as currently Americans
are eligible for Medicare at 65. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
