<HEADLINE> Draft Protocol on Hazardous Wastes Ready for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Delegates from 87 countries
have made progress in elaborating a protocol on transboundary
movements of hazardous wastes and their disposal, according to a
news release reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The release issued by the United Nations Environment Program
(UNEP) said that the draft text of the protocol will be forwarded
to the Fifth Meeting of the Conference of the Parties (COP-5) of
the Basel Convention for further negotiation this week.
</P>
<P>
If adopted and ratified, the protocol will for the first time
establish a rigorous system for assigning liability in the event
of an accident involving hazardous wastes. It will also place a
limit on the financial liability.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations started in 1993 as a response to the concerns
of developing countries about their lack of financial and
technological capacity for cleaning up unwanted hazardous waste
dumps and spills on their territory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
