<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks End Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks moved
lower on profit-taking Tuesday despite encouragement of two merger
announcements.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 44.32 at
11,034.13. The Blue chip index rose 235.24 points Friday, marking
its second-largest point gain of the year.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 6.79 at 1,350.45 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 5.85 at 2,837.26.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the S&AMP;P rose 38.13 points while the Nasdaq
rocketed 108.87, or 3.98 percent, its largest single-day point
gain in its history.
</P>
<P>
Two mergers sparked trading but did not drive the whole market
higher. Viacom Inc. is buying CBS Corp. for 34.45 billion U.S.
dollars in stock in the biggest media deal ever and Hilton hotels
Corp. is merging Promus Hotel Corp. in a 4 billion dollars deal,
creating one of the biggest lodging chains in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE Index fell 2.18 at 623.71. But the American Stock
Exchange Index rose 7.28 at 793.67 and the Russell 2000 Index of
smaller companies rose 2.27 at 438.24.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,667 down, 1,347 up and 537
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 707.30 million shares from 654.54
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Stock markets were closed Monday for the Labor Day holiday.
</P>
