<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands Cuts all Aid to Kenya For Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands will cut all
aid to Kenya within the next three years due to its bad
governance, Jelte van Wieren, first secretary of the Royal
Netherlands Embassy in Kenya, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Wieren said Kenya had failed to meet requirements for continued
 bilateral aid due to its bad governance, human rights abuses and
impeded democratization, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
"Whereas the level of poverty in Kenya remains high, the
country will not get further funding due to failure to implement
policies and lack of good governance," Wieren told the press
before the opening of the World Press Photo Exhibition in Mombasa,
a port city in southeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He said the Dutch Minister for Development Cooperation was in
Kenya recently to brief the Kenyan President on the stand adopted
on severing future bilateral aid.
</P>
<P>
The first secretary noted that bilateral aid to Kenya stood at
an original level of 54 million U.S. dollars for the past decade,
but was scaled down to 24 million U.S. dollars last year. In the
next three years, it will be all phased out.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government had reviewed its initial bilateral
aid policy with 78 nations and would only continue to support 17,
adding that Tanzania and Uganda were among the countries that
would continue to get bilateral aid from the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"The level of economic development in these countries is
positive due to their good policy implementation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition of entries for this year's World Press Photo
contest opened Tuesday at the Mombasa Old Law Courts for the
first time in Kenya, and will run for two weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
