<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders Independent Probe into Waco Siege </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno has asked Republican former Senator John Danforth to inquire
independently into the government's use of force against the
Branch Davidian cult in Waco, Texas, government sources said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Danforth, 63, served as attorney general in Missouri for eight
years before entering the Senate. He retired from the Senate in
January.
</P>
<P>
Reno's decision came as congressional Republicans have
increased pressure on her and on FBI director Louis Freeh to
explain how evidence, including a videotape, about the siege was
withheld from the public for years.
</P>
<P>
The Republican Party tries to find out whether the FBI lied
about using incendiary tear gas canisters during the final raid on
the cult compound in Waco. More than 80 cult members died in the
raid.
</P>
<P>
The FBI revealed recently that it fired several flammable tear
gas canisters at the compound hours before the main Branch
Davidian building went up in flames in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The FBI and the Justice Department had previously denied use
of any incendiary devices.
</P>
<P>
The independent investigations are expected to focus on whether
this misinformation was the result of a bureaucratic slip-up or a
coverup.
</P>
<P>
The Republican Party have used the recent revelations to
attack the credibility of Reno and the Justice Department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denktash's Statements on Cyprus Issue Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government
Wednesday firmly refused to condition the start of peace talks on
the recognition of the breakway Turkish Cypriot republic in
northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou said that if Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash and his supporter Turkey insist on
"the recognition of the illegal regime" in northern Cyprus as a
condition to start talks, no initiative on Cyprus will be able to
take place.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou said that "if this is Mr. Denktash and Turkey's
final position, then there can not be any talks, initiative or a
solution to the Cyprus issue."
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that Denktash will "finally change his
views, come to his senses," so that the Cyprus issue will be
settled.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Turkish Cypriots-controlled north
and Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" which is only recognized by
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou's remarks came in response to statements made by
Denktash in Washington.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the Strategic and International Studies Center,
Denktash said he will not enter negotiations for a Cyprus
settlement unless "the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" is
recognized.
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that the only prescribed solution for Cyprus is
the establishment of a confederation of two states, which had been
staunchly rejected by the Cyprus' government and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island in a
bi-communal federation formula, but the talks between the two
rival sides have been stalled since 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader also criticized the G-8, which
groups the U.S., France, Britain, Germany, Italy, Canada, Japan,
the seven most industrialized nations, and Russia, for rejecting
"the existence of the Turkish Cypriot community."
</P>
<P>
The G-8, in their Cologne summit in June, requested
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to invite the leaders of the two
sides to unconditional negotiations in the autumn of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
