<HEADLINE> Highlights of Today's Diplomatic News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights
of the diplomatic news released by Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
NPC Chairman Meets Nepalese Former PM
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC), met with Sher Bahadur Deupa,
former prime minister of Nepal, at the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed thanks for the Nepalese Government's support to
China on world issues, and for its firm stand on the issues of
Tibet and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Deupa thanked the Chinese Government and people for China's
assistance to Nepal in its economic development and efforts to
maintain sovereignty, and congratulated China on the 50th
anniversary of its founding on October 1 and the upcoming return
of Macao.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed Nepal's unswavering position on the Tibet and
Taiwan issues, stressing that Nepal will never allow any foreign
forces to use its territory to engage in activities against China.
</P>
<P>
Cote D'Ivoire PM Leaves China
</P>
<P>
Daniel Kablan Duncan, Prime Minister of Cote D'Ivoire, left
here for Paris after attending the 22nd Congress of the Universal
Postal Union.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and Vice-President Hu Jintao and
other senior Chinese officials met with him on different occasions
during his stay here.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Tanzanian Visitors
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing met with Muhammed Seif Khatib,
minister of state of Tanzania, and his party here.
</P>
<P>
Li cited Tanzania as an old friend of China and expressed his
hope that the ties of cooperation between the peoples of the two
countries would be constantly strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Meets IBM Chairman
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing met here with Louis Gerstner Jr.
, chairman of the IBM Corporation of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Li praised IBM's participation in the development of China's
information industry, and expressed the hope that the company
would strengthen cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Gerstner gave a briefing on IBM's business in China, saying
that his company would like to expand its involvement with China's
IT industry.
</P>
<P>
Chinese, Guinean Military Leaders Meet
</P>
<P>
Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian met with Ibrahima Diallo,
chief of general staff of the Guinean army.
</P>
<P>
Chi said that although the two countries are far away, the
friendship between the two peoples goes back to ancient times.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also vice chairman of the Central Military Commission and
state councilor, said that as two developing countries, China and
Guinea have common interests in many aspects and have reached
consensus on important international matters.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes Diallo's China visit will be successful.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Defense Minister Meets Vietnamese Guests
</P>
<P>
While meeting with Nguyen Phuc Thanh, vice chairman of the
National Assembly of Vietnam, Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian
said that China and Vietnam follow the leadership of the communist
parties and are in the process of reform and opening up.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral exchanges in national defense and security
between the two sides benefit not only the basic interests of the
two peoples, but also world peace and regional stability, said Chi,
also vice chairman of the Central Military Commission and state
councilor. 
</P>
