<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia May Review Participation in Kosovo Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Russian official said
Wednesday that Moscow might take a new look at its participation
in the Kosovo peacekeeping operation unless progress is made in
ensuring stability in the Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
"The Federation Council might reconsider the form of Russia's
participation in the operation, unless progress is made in
ensuring stability in the region, or Kosovo's secession from
Yugoslavia becomes imminent with the subsequent creation of a mono-
ethnic state," said Leonid Ivashov, head of the Defense Ministry's
International Cooperation Department.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been critical of NATO peacekeeping forces' slow
progress in disarming the Kosovo Liberation Army and the
protection of ethnic Serbs there.
</P>
<P>
NATO forces have failed to ensure the safety of the people
living in the territory, primarily that of non-Albanians, Ivashov
said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the disarmament process of the KLA is unsatisfactory.
The KLA is unlikely to turn in its arms by the scheduled date of
September 19, he said.
</P>
<P>
"No serious disarmament of the KLA is underway, therefore it
is pointless to speak about any sort of stability in the region,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia has some 3,600 troops in Kosovo as part of a 40,000
multinational peacekeeping force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
