<HEADLINE> Canadian PM Declares Readiness for Tackling Y2K Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien has declared 99 percent of the work in his government
ready for the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement released late Tuesday, the prime minister
said that "99 percent of the work on essential federal services is
complete" to make the country a world leader in tackling the Year
2000 computer challenge.
</P>
<P>
The readiness covers services such as Old Age Security, the
Canada Pension Plan, the Customs Border Services, GST credits,
Employment Insurance and Child Tax Benefits, according to the
announcement. 
