<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues Opening-up: Wu Yi (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 8 (Xinhua)-- China will continue to actively
develop economic and trade cooperation throughout the world, State
Councillor Wu Yi said here today.
</P>
<P>
Wu, who is also an alternate member of the Political Bureau of
the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, made the
remarks in her address at the "Symposium on International
Investment Cooperation in the 21st Century" held in this coastal
city.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that China will continue to push forward investment and
trade liberalization in the Asia-Pacific region, actively expand
opening-up, and promote economic and trade contacts and mutually
beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
This will be done by adhering to China's status as a developing
country, taking into consideration its national conditions and in
line with the principle of equality between rights and obligations,
she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to Wu, China has successfully warded off the Asian
financial crisis and sustained the high-speed growth of its
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The results indicate that the Chinese government's policy to
stimulate the national economy has paid off, she said, adding that
China's economic growth also made its due contribution to the
stability of other Asian economies, even the world economy as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that China has not slowed down its steps to open
wider, even during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that the use of overseas capital is an
important part of China's opening-up policy, and the foreign
investment played an important role in China's economic growth and
the reform and opening-up cause.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China boasts political and social stability,
sustained economic growth, stable currency and sufficient foreign
exchange reserve, she said. These factors combined make the
comprehensive investment cost quite low in China, turning the
country an attractive destination for overseas investors, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
