agreed Tuesday to buy CBS Corp. in a 38 billion stock deal that
would join some of the biggest cable TV networks with the most-
watched broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
-- A Swiss investigation has uncovered evidence that a
construction company that received major Kremlin contracts paid
tens of thousands of dollars of bills charged to credit cards in
the names of Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his two daughters.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Vice President Al Gore proposed Tuesday to guarantee
access to affordable health insurance for all children by 2005,
expanding on a program enacted two years ago that he conceded had
had limited success so far.
</P>
<P>
-- As many as 200,000 people, nearly a quarter of East Timor's
population, have been driven from their homes within the last four
days by militias opposed to independence for the territory, U.N.
Secretary General's spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Global Crossing Ltd., an undersea-cable operator, is
expected to unveil a venture with Microsoft Corp. and Japan's
Softbank Corp. to build an advanced telecommunications network in
Asia, according to people familiar with the situation.
</P>
<P>
-- A powerful earthquake rocked Athens, killing at least 30
people and leaving more than 100 missing. Most of the damage from
the quake, which measured 5.9 on the Richter scale, was
concentrated in working-class and immigrant areas north of the
Greek capital, near the Tremor's epicenter.  
