<HEADLINE> Manila Postpones Polls in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada signed into law Wednesday a measure postponing the
elections of the Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM) from
September 13, 1999, to the second Monday of September 2000.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony held at the Presidential
Palace, Estrada said the postponement of the elections will give
ARMM Governor Nur Misuari more time to bring peace and development
to Mindanao and the Southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The president added that he signed the law also because a
plebiscite ratifying the proposed New Organic Act of the
autonomous region must precede any elections.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the proposed New Organic Act is yet pending in
Congress, he said there is nothing to ratify and therefore there
can be no elections this month.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony, the president said he was heartened by the
news that the government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation
Front signed an interim agreement last week to start formal peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the agreement will bring a "stable political
environment" that is vital for Mindanao to attain peace and
progress.
</P>
<P>
Estrada reiterated his pledge to transform Mindanao from a land
of promise to a land of fulfillment during his term which ends in
2004.
</P>
<P>
In keeping with his vow, he said the proposed budget for the
year 2000, which the administration submitted to Congress, gives
Mindanao the highest per capita allocation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
