<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Announces Ban on Wax-Burning Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Regional Services
Department (RSD) Wednesday announced a ban on wax-burning
activities during the Mid-Autumn Festival, a traditional Chinese
one which falls on September 24 this year.
</P>
<P>
The department will step up enforcement action against those
burning wax at any pleasure ground or gazetted beach during the
festival, a RSD spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"Wax-burning activities must be severely dealt with because hot
steam and wax, going out of control, will not only stain, char and
damage facilities but also cause severe burns to players
themselves and innocent people in the vicinity," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
To prevent such tragic incidents, the RSD has recently put up
anti-wax burning posters at all pleasure grounds and gazetted
beaches, and informed school principals in writing to convey the
message to their students, he said.
</P>
<P>
With regard to enforcement action, the spokesman said that not
less than 500 staff would be deployed to patrol the venues on each
of the nights of September 23, 24 and 25.
</P>
<P>
"Prosecutions will be taken out against those who do not abide
by the law and ignore warnings given by our staff," he said,
adding that last year, more than 14,000 people were verbally
warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
