<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin on Sino-Australian Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese President
Jiang Zemin stressed here Wednesday the need for China and
Australia to undertake efforts to build a Sino-Australian
relationship oriented towards the new century.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at a welcoming luncheon hosted in his honor by
Australian Prime Minister John Howard, Jiang said he saw the need
for the two countries to undertake the following efforts:
</P>
<P>
Firstly, to have a firm grasp on the bigger picture of the
bilateral relationship and constantly expand common interests by
standing at a strategic high ground and proceeding from the long-
term interests of the two peoples;
</P>
<P>
Secondly, to elevate, in a pioneering and innovative spirit,
the interflow and cooperation between the two countries in the
economic, trade, scientific and technological fields to a new
level;
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, to strengthen consultations and coordination on
regional and international issues and make more contribution to
peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific and the world at large;
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, to properly approach and handle the differences and
divergences between the two countries and promote a sound and
stable development of the bilateral relations according to the
principles of treating each other as equals and seeking common
ground while shelving differences;
</P>
<P>
Fifthly, to increase personnel exchanges between the two
countries at different levels and promote mutual understanding
between the two peoples so as to foster a solid foundation for the
development of Sino-Australian relations.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Jiang said China and Australia share broad
interests in developing their respective economies and promoting
regional and global peace and development.
</P>
<P>
He said the economies of the two countries, with their
distinctive features, are highly complementary to each other.
Therefore, he said, there is a huge potential and a broad prospect
for exchanges and cooperation between the two sides in the
economic and trade, scientific and technological and educational
fields.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president said important progress has been made in
the bilateral relations with frequent exchange of high-level
visits and close consultations and dialogues in various areas. The
steadily expanding economic and trade cooperation have made the
two countries important partners to each other.
</P>
<P>
All these exchanges and cooperation have benefited the Chinese
and Australian people and contributed to the stability and
prosperity in the Asia-Pacific region, Jiang said, adding "We are
fully confident about the development prospect of the bilateral
relationship."
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that as long as our two sides take a longer
view by standing on a higher ground and join hands with each other,
we will surely be able to bring a sound Sino-Australian
relationship into the 21st century," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Howard said at the luncheon that President Jiang's visit to
Australia, the first by a Chinese head of state to the country, is
of great importance to the development of relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said Australia and China, both members of Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation, are countries of major influence in the Asia-
Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Relations between them, based on mutual respect, acknowledgment
of differences and attaching importance to common ground between
them, are now in the best period in history, said Howard.
</P>
<P>
Howard also reiterated Australia's one-China policy.
</P>
<P>
He said Australia supports China's entry into the World Trade
Organization and the two sides have completed bilateral talks on
China's access to the organization. Australia will continue to
make efforts to strive for China's entry into the WTO as early as
possible, he added.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the luncheon, Jiang also met with Australian Senate
President Margaret Reid and House Speaker Neil Andrew. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
