<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Bans Duty-free Import of Meat Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada approved Wednesday a ban on the importation and sale of
chicken, pork and beef by duty-free shops.
</P>
<P>
The directive was based on Agriculture Secretary Edgardo
Angara's recommendation to stop the duty-free importation of these
products which poses unfair competitive to local producers.
</P>
<P>
Angara said local livestock and poultry producers have
expressed concern over the importation of these meat products
citing the inability of duty-free authorities to restrict their
sale within duty-free zones.
</P>
<P>
He said the share of duty-free shop's importation of these
products has also been found to be unusually high relative to
total imports.
</P>
<P>
As of August 1999, importation by duty-free shops accounted for
33 percent of total chicken imports, 11 percent of pork imports
and 9 percent of beef imports.
</P>
<P>
Angara said since those imported and sold by duty-free shops
are not covered by the minimum access volume (MAV) setup, this
does not support the agriculture sector to become more efficient
and competitive.
</P>
<P>
The MAV, which varies per commodity, is the import volume of a
farm product given low tariff rates.
</P>
<P>
As legally provided, the quantity allowed to be imported should
be equivalent to only three percent of a country's consumption of
that product.
</P>
<P>
For 1999, tariff for chicken has been pegged at 45 percent,
pork at 30 percent and beef at 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
For imports outside the MAV, tariff for chicken and pork has
been placed at 60 percent while beef, which has been liberalized,
is levied a 30 percent tariff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
