<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: As Honeymoon Over, Economic Headaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 8 (Xinhua) -- One-hundred days after
taking office, Nepali Prime Minister Krishna Prasad Bhattarai has
drawn both praise and criticism for his performance.
</P>
<P>
The new government came into office on May 31 after the Nepali
Congress, the largest party in the country, won a comfortable
majority in the parliamentary election in early May.
</P>
<P>
Judging from the performance of the new government in the first
100 days, it appeared to have been on the course to fulfill its
promises.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai has reiterated his commitment that he will try to
change the face of the country within a period of three years. "I
am aiming for a tangible change in the living conditions of
average Nepalese," he said after he took office.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai's government has been focusing on solving the
pressing problems faced by the country, including poverty,
corruption, unemployment and the ultra-leftist guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
"My first and last priority is to root out corruption in
Nepal," Bhattarai told reporters the other day. "Those amassing
wealth beyond their reasonable means and found guilty of
corruption will be punished not only with prosecution, but also
with other instruments of deterrence," he said.
</P>
<P>
In its policies and programs presented at a joint sitting of
the parliament on July 1, the government identified poverty
alleviation as one of its priorities.
</P>
<P>
To meet its aim of poverty alleviation, the government has
brought up a campaign called Bishweshwar Among the Poor. The
program aims to help 20,000 absolutely poor families with soft
loans of up to 30,000 rupees (about 529 U.S. dollars) at 5 percent
interest rate to enable them to have access to integrated
facilities of shelter, income-generating schemes and the kind.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining law and order is another priority of the
government. To contain the ultra-leftist guerrillas who have been
causing unrest in some part of Nepal since 1996, the government
has introduced the Ganeshman Peace Campaign, which aims to help
those who give up the path of violence and terror and return to
lead a lawful and normal life.
</P>
<P>
The government has also taken other steps to get the country
out of heaps of problems, such as banning the polluting
three-wheeled vehicles to prevent air pollution, and implementing
the value-added tax to enlarge the income base, among others.
</P>
<P>
But there have been doubts whether the government's priorities
will be translated into actions.
</P>
<P>
Given all those problems and the dismal reality of the country,
the task of the new government is no less challenging than that of
the previous ones, even though it is a majority government which
is likely to enjoy stability for a considerable long time.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has seen six minority or coalition governments since 1994
because of political instability.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is one of the poorest countries in the world, with about
45 percent of the country's 22 million population living below the
poverty line, and a per capita annual income of 200 dollars. And
only 40 percent of the people can read and write.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth was 2.1 percent in 1998, below the
population growth of 2.4 percent. The country had a fiscal deficit
estimated at 300 million dollars in 1998/1999. And about 60
percent of the development projects funds come from donors.
</P>
<P>
With numerous constraints and limited resources at disposal,
the present government faces a tough road.
</P>
<P>
"People expect religious-minded Bhattarai to take some drastic
actions towards achieving the goal of poverty alleviation, but it
is not being taken up," columnist Dhruvahari Adhikary wrote in a
weekly on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"He promised to change the face of the country in three years,
but because of the decision to add one more weekly holiday, the
goal has now turned into a six-year plan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Still there are some optimistic views about the Bhattarai
government.
</P>
<P>
Columnist Naresh Joshi wrote in The Rising Nepal Tuesday that
though the government faces a host of challenges, it is also
invested with hopes from the people.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Bhattarai's image and reputation as a man keen
to get things done is high. His political stature within and
outside the NC (Nepali Congress) inspires confidence among the
people that the Bhattarai cabinet will be in the business of
improving the quality of life of an average Nepali," Joshi wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Chairman of the Palestine Electricity Company Saeed
Khouri disclosed that his company had signed Monday a contract for
the establishment of an electricity generating plant in the
Palestinian self-rule territories with the Belgian ABP company.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Arab daily Al Hayat quoted Khouri as saying that
the implementation of the project will take about 12 months, and
that production of electricity will start in September 2000.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The Tunisian capital city of Tunis will host an
exhibition of petroleum and natural gas industry in February 2000,
bringing together the North African states of Egypt, Libya,
Algeria, Morocco and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
The event will include a convention to discuss issues of
concerns of the region, as well as ways to develop and consolidate
the petroleum and gas industries in the North African states.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT -- Eight Kuwaiti contracting companies have won
contracts to the tune of 60 million Kuwaiti dinars (193.5 million
U.S. dollars) for the construction of the infrastructure for
housing projects in south of Al Jahraa and Gleib Al Shioukh.
</P>
<P>
According to Wednesday's local press reports, the contracts
stipulate the construction of roads, drainage system, electricity,
water and communications in these areas.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A new river port will be established along the
Ismailia stream at the city of Belbeis to serve investment
projects of the Tenth of Ramadan industrial town, within the
framework of developing navigation in the Ismailia stream and
linking it with the ports of Suez, Port Said, and east Suez gulf.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Alam Al Yom quoted the Egyptian Minister of
Transport and Communications Soliman Metwalli as saying that the
project will cost 200 million pounds (about 58 million dollars),
and aims at facilitating the shipment of 8 million tons of goods a
year through the Suez Canal and the Ismailia stream.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian Al Massa'iya (Evening Daily) Tuesday
reported that a joint Israeli-Jordanian-Turkish factory for cotton
textiles has started to market its production in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The factory was put up in Al Hussein industrial town at a total
cost of 160 million dollars, constituting the first outcome of
joint Israeli-Turkish-Jordanian cooperation.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's industrial exports to foreign markets have
reached 262 million dollars in the first eight months of 1999, 31
percent higher than 345 million dollars in the corresponding
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
A statement by Ibrahim Fawzi, president of the General
Investment Authority and Free Zones, said exports of industrial
goods are due to rise to over 500 million dollars by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Dutch electronics manufacturer Philips has
announced that it would step up efforts to grab a larger share of
the mobile phone market in the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
According to an industry report, currently there are
approximately 3.5 million cellular phone service subscribers in the
Middle East. The leading market is Saudi Arabia, followed by
Lebanon and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The total number of mobile phone users in the UAE at the end of
June was 378,139. 
</P>
</TEXT>
