<HEADLINE> Roundup: Preparations for Macao SAR Well Under Way (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- With only some 100 days left
till Macao's return to the motherland, preparations for setting up
the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR) have been going on
smoothly in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive and leading officials of the future SAR
have been decided and they are busy paving the way for the sound
operation of the SAR government to be established on December 20
this year.
</P>
<P>
With overwhelming votes, 44-year-old banker Edmund Ho Hau Wah
beat the other candidate and won the chief executive election on
May 15. And he received the certificate of appointment in Beijing
from Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji on May 24.
</P>
<P>
During the two months after that, Edmund Ho conducted extensive
consultations among local residents about choosing the SAR's
leading officials.
</P>
<P>
On August 11, the State Council of China announced the
appointment of seven SAR government officials and the procurator-
general of the SAR on the basis of nomination of Edmund Ho.
</P>
<P>
The eight people, aged between 41 to 50, are all permanent
Macao residents and six are civil servants of the current
Portuguese Macao government. Most of them hold doctor's or master'
s degrees.
</P>
<P>
Since the appointment of the chief executive and his
subordinates, they have shouldered the expectation and
responsibility of materializing the concept of "Macao people
governing Macao" and bringing about a promising future.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to be honest and diligent in serving the
residents, to improve public security and revitalize the local
economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
