<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Literacy Program Makes Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has been implementing
an Education for All (EFA) program covering formal and non-formal
education which have turned 100,000 illiterates into literates
since the World Conference on Education for All held in Thailand
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The country has also drawn up a specific program for the year
2000, said Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt, first secretary of the
Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, at a ceremony held
here Wednesday to mark the International Literacy Day.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 660,000 illiterates in 145 EFA townships
in Myanmar. Of the 240,000 learners, over 100,000 have become
literate.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Khin Nyunt, who is also chairman of the
Myanmar Education Committee, stressed the need to provide
continuing education to those who have obtained basic literacy.
</P>
<P>
Continuing education covers literacy promotion, income
generation and better life programs through reading circles,
libraries and community learning centers.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a Myanmar Literacy Resource Center (MLRC)
will be set up in the near future with the technical and financial
assistance of the Asia-Pacific Culture Center for the U.N.
Education, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
He anticipated that the MLRC will be able to extend and expand
the literacy program in Myanmar. He emphasized the need for
effective implementation of the EFA program in the country with
active community participation to improve the health, fitness and
education standard of the Myanmar people.
</P>
<P>
The literacy rate of Myanmar in the early 19th century was
significantly high compared with some other countries.
</P>
<P>
After regaining independence in 1948, Myanmar, with a
population of approximately 17 million then, had a literacy rate
of only 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar promulgated the Mass Education Law in 1948 and firstly
introduced the illiteracy eradication program, followed by a
national literacy campaign in 1964.
</P>
<P>
These literacy campaigns enabled 24 million of the people aged
15 and above to become literate.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar was awarded the Mohammed Reza Pahlavi Literacy Prize in
1971 and the Noma Prize in 1983 by the UNESCO for the success of
its literacy campaign.
</P>
<P>
Attending Wednesday's ceremony were representatives from
Myanmar government departments, non-governmental organizations and
U.N. agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
