<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Dips Beyond 40 Against U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Peso depreciated
to 40.150 pesos against the U.S. dollar on Wednesday, breaking the
psychological level of 40 pesos to one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the local currency closed at 39.775 pesos against
the greenback at the Philippine Dealing System.
</P>
<P>
Traders blamed both internal and external factors to the
depreciation of the currency, which has recovered from last year's
unprecedented low level of 45 pesos against the greenback to 37-39
pesos level since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
They said the country's low interest policy increased liquidity
of the local currency while decreasing its value against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's unstable political situation triggered
mainly by the disputes of the Charter change also worried local
and foreign traders and attributed to the depreciation of the
peso.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the rates hike of the United States, the
risk of East Timor and the depreciation of other Asian currencies
also prompted fund managers to convert their holdings into dollars
which carried more stable yields.
</P>
<P>
Rafael Buenaventura, governor of the Central Bank of the
Philippines, said earlier he might raise bank reserve requirements
or take other measures if the local currency breaches the 40 pesos
to one dollar psychological level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
