<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak FM Criticizes U.S. Laws on Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz Wednesday criticized foreign legislation and American
laws banning imports of goods being allegedly manufactured by
children.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a two-day conference on "The State of Child Labor
in South Asia" here, Aziz said these laws need to clearly define
the child labor.
</P>
<P>
Referring to criticism by some western countries of Pakistan's
soccer industry for the involvement of children in football
manufacturing, Aziz said that 93 percent of child labor has been
removed from this industry, but soccer import is still banned
under the U.S. laws.
</P>
<P>
He called for the effective implementation of the law
formulated for reducing and checking the practice of child labor
as well as raising the age of child from 14 to 15 years old in
terms of child labor laws.
</P>
<P>
He noted that significant progress has been made towards the
elimination of child labor. However, a lot still needs to be done
for the welfare of children in Pakistan, he added.
</P>
<P>
"It is the responsibility of the government to provide its
youth with the best available opportunities and possibilities,
where they can prosper and become useful members of the society,"
said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that child labor is prevalent in most of the
developing countries as well as in some of the developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a problem that is peculiar to any particular area or
region of the world," he said, adding "child labor is the directed
result of the prevailing endemic poverty that forces the child to
labor," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
