<BODY>
<HEADLINE> List of Terms of Annual APEC Leaders Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, NEW ZEALAND, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The following is
a list of terms that are frequently used in the annual informal
meetings of leaders of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) forum.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
APEC -- Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation:
</P>
<P>
APEC was established in 1989 in response to the growing
interdependence among Asia Pacific economies. It is a grouping of
21 regional economies set up to improve the stability, security
and prosperity of its peoples. Begun as an informal dialogue
group, APEC has since become the primary regional vehicle for
promoting free and open trade and investment, and practical
economic and technical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABAC -- APEC Business Advisory Council:
</P>
<P>
In 1995, APEC Economic Leaders established a permanent council
composed of up to three senior business people from each member
economy to provide advice on implementation of APEC action plans
and on the specific business sector priorities.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATL -- Accelerated Tariff Liberalization:
</P>
<P>
The Early Voluntary Sectoral Liberalization (EVSL) initiative
sought to liberalize trade in 15 key sectors ahead of the Bogor
2010/2020 timetable. At Kuala Lumpur, participating economies
agreed to transfer the tariff elements of the first nine sectors
to the WTO to broaden participation and seek binding negotiations.
</P>
<P>
As APEC Chair, New Zealand is coordinating discussion of those
elements, now known as the ATL initiative, in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAP - - Collective Action Plans:
</P>
<P>
The Manila Action Plan for APEC (MAPA), adopted by APEC Leaders
in 1996, includes the Individual and Collective Action Plans and
progress reports on joint activities outlined in Bogor. CAPs
essentially are "business plans" where APEC members collectively
outline plans for trade and investment liberalization, business
facilitation and ECOTECH in 14 areas: tariffs; non-tariff
measures; services; investment; standards and conformance; customs
procedures; intellectual property rights; competition policy and
law; deregulation; government procurement; rules of origin;
dispute mediation; mobility of business people; and implementation
of the WTO Uruguay Round.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CTI -- Committee on Trade and Investment:
</P>
<P>
The CTI, established in November 1993, coordinates APEC's work
on liberalizing and facilitating trade and investment. It works
to reduce impediments to business activity in 14 specific areas,
including tariff and non-tariff measures, services, intellectual
property rights, competition policy and dispute mediation.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ECOTECH -- Economic and Technical Cooperation:
</P>
<P>
APEC's third pillar, economic and technical cooperation (trade
and investment liberalization and facilitation make up the first
and second pillars), covers a variety of capacity-building
activities conducted by APEC bodies. These are aimed at enhancing
members' -- especially developing members' -- ability to benefit
from the liberalization agenda and reducing disparities within the
diverse APEC region.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
IAP -- Individual Action Plans:
</P>
<P>
The Manila Action Plan for APEC (MAPA), adopted by APEC Leaders
in 1996, includes the Individual and Collective Action Plans and
progress reports on joint activities outlined in Bogor. IAPs are
the central mechanism by which each economy outlines their plans
for trade and investment liberalization, business facilitation and
ECOTECH in 14 areas: tariffs, non-tariff measures; services;
investment; standards and conformance; customs procedures;
intellectual property rights; competition policy and law;
deregulation; government procurement; rules of origin, dispute
mediation; mobility of business people; and implementation of the
WTO Uruguay Round.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SOM -- Senior Officials' Meeting:
</P>
<P>
SOMs are held regularly throughout the year. APEC senior
officials make recommendations to the Ministers and carry out
their decisions. They oversee and coordinate, with the approval
from ministers, the budgets and work programs of the APEC fora.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
