<HEADLINE> Rwanda Police Officers Seek Training From Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda has requested
Tanzania to train its police officers because Rwanda's police
force is not enough to handle the ever-increasing crime rate at
home.
</P>
<P>
Principal Secretary of the Rwandan Ministry of Home Affairs,
Seif Kamazi, made the request while meeting Tanzania's Inspector
General of Police, Omar Mahita, in Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Local media Wednesday quoted Kamazi as saying that the current
size of the police force in his country is largely made up of
military and non- military personnel.
</P>
<P>
Kamazi's delegation, which is in Tanzania for one-week visit,
is scheduled to tour a police college in north Tanzania's Moshi
town.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan delegation is looking into the possibility of
bringing students for training at the college, which accommodates
2,000 students, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda will also seek for Tanzanian tutors to teach at its
newly introduced police college at Gishali. The college has a
capacity of accommodating 700 students.  
</P>
</TEXT>
