<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Financial Aid to Overseas-Funded Businesses:Ministry Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China will allow eligible
overseas-financed businesses to issue A shares (for domestic
investors) or B shares (for overseas investors), Ma Xiuhong,
Assistant Minister of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference on investment policies at the
ongoing third China Fair for Investment and Trade, which opened
today in Xiamen, Fujian Province, Ma said that China would also
provide overseas investors who are funding State-favored sectors,
such as energy and transportation, with insurance policies against
potential risk.
</P>
<P>
Also revealed were a range of other new measures to give more
financial aid to overseas-backed firms in China, including the
establishment of a special industrial investment fund which would
ease the shortage of Chinese investors' equity stake in joint
ventures when overseas investors add funding.
</P>
<P>
When overseas-backed businesses borrow money inside China,
Chinese banks will be allowed to receive guarantees from overseas
share-holders, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
But loans in Chinese currency obtained by using guarantees from
overseas share-holders and from hard currencies should be in line
with China's industrial development policies. These loans can be
used to invest in fixed assets and used as working capital, and
must not be used to purchase foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded businesses will be permitted to use foreign
investors' assets abroad as mortgages at overseas branches of
Chinese banks, and they will get the need-based loans given by the
Chinese banks' overseas branches or domestic branches.
</P>
<P>
The China Fair for Investment and Trade, the third annual event,
runs from September 8-12.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
