<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Y2K Ironed out in Kenya's Mombasa Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Mombasa Port, the major one
along the Indian Ocean in southeastern Kenya, has announced that
it will be open for business as usual across the period of the Y2K
date change.
</P>
<P>
Mombasa is among the first of the world's major ports to make
such an announcement, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the confidence of the port to do so stems
not only from its own highly successful Y2K program but also from
its adherence to international standards and best practice.
</P>
<P>
By following the guidelines laid down by the International
Maritime Organization (IMO) and working closely to the standards
set by their colleagues in Hong Kong Port, Mombasa Port's Y2K team
has done tremendous work over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The compliance in turn provides the reassurance the
international shipping industry needs in order to plan its own Y2K
working arrangement.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K compliance for the port covers its cargo handling
equipment, its computer systems, its communications and general
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the ships have to attain the IMO's
certification of Y2K readiness, involving the entire vessels from
navigation systems through engines to safety and support
equipment. They must also carry a Y2K due diligence log.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that after September 30, 1999, vessels not
possession of the IMO certification and due diligence logs will be
refused entry to Mombasa Port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
