<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Doctors Strike on Colleague Conviction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's doctors Wednesday
staged a nation-wide strike to protest a verdict by a Beirut
military court that sentenced three doctors for negligence.
</P>
<P>
Doctors across the country heeded the Medical Syndicate's
call, stopping work for the day and dealing only with urgent
cases.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of physicians in white robe picketed the Lebanese
parliament in downtown Beirut to demand a legislation that
immunizes the medical profession against prosecution without
scientific evidence.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the demonstrators will meet House Speaker
Nabih Berri to extend their demands.
</P>
<P>
The military tribunal Tuesday night sentenced the three
accused doctors to five days in jail each for their negligence
which led to the death of an army sergeant.
</P>
<P>
Since the three doctors had spent more than one week in
custody during the investigation, they were released after the
trial.
</P>
<P>
The trial was the first of its kind in Lebanon's military
court history because the country does not have laws that pertain
specifically to medical malpractice and dissatisfied patients or
their families usually have to resort to civil courts.
</P>
<P>
The case sparked strong protest and criticism from the
country's medical associations.
</P>
<P>
Ghattas Khouryt, the head of Medical Syndicate for Beirut and
North Lebanon, said "we are not against doctors facing up to their
responsibilities, but we don't accept that they be treated like
criminals."
</P>
<P>
"We are against their arrest, because we know this will create
a crisis between doctors and patients," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lectures and Homework Efficient But Unlovely: Student Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey of Chinese
primary and middle school students shows that while they'll admit
lectures and homework are a good way to learn, they would prefer a
livelier curriculum that involves hands-on experience, computer-
assisted training, and out-of-class reading of their favorite
subjects.
</P>
<P>
"The old-fashioned, 'efficient' learning techniques are meant
to help students cope with exams," says Dr. Zheng Xinrong of
Beijing Normal University, who headed the survey sponsored by the
China Juvenile Research Center (CJRC). "Most students cannot
improve their efficiency through their favorite style of learning.
"
</P>
<P>
More than 3,000 students from Beijing, Tianjin, and Shanghai
municipalities, and Liaoning, Shaanxi, Shandong, Jiangxi, Henan,
Sichuan and Guangdong provinces answered the questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
"It's human nature, especially the nature of children, to
acquire knowledge through hands-on learning. But the Chinese
educational system is yet to highlight this active way of studying,
" Zheng says.
</P>
<P>
In today's information age, rote memorization is no longer as
effective for young people and has been knocked off its pedestal
by experiential learning, says Dr. Zheng.
</P>
<P>
However, standard-answer tests have long been a feature of
China's education system, she says, and are still believed to be
the best preparation for difficult exams.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the parents polled agreed their children
should take the initiative to determine which learning style
offers the best fit, but they worried that students who study by
themselves might be wasting their time.
</P>
<P>
"Most students and their parents do believe that the
traditional way of memorizing is out of date," Dr. Zheng says. "
But the reality of the Chinese exam-evaluation system cannot make
their ideal choice of a learning style a possibility, at least for
now."
</P>
<P>
She says that the key to developing a quality education system
in China is to re-structure the current one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
