<HEADLINE> Jobless Japanese Man Stabs 8 People, Killing 2 in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A Japanese man stabbed eight
people at random in a bustling district in Tokyo on Wednesday
morning, killing two and injuring six others, police said.
</P>
<P>
The victims, including five men and three women, were stabbed
in the downtown Ikebukuro district. They were taken to hospital,
where two of them died later.
</P>
<P>
Of the six others, one sustained serious injuries, while the
remaining five suffered minor injuries, police said.
</P>
<P>
Police identified the assailant as Hiroshi Zoda, a 23-year-old
without a job or a fixed address.
</P>
<P>
The suspect apparently first attacked people coming up by
escalator to the ground floor of a large-scale do-it-yourself
store and then went onto a street, swinging a knife at passers-by,
police said.
</P>
<P>
Zoda, who was later seized by passers-by and arrested initially
on suspicion of attempted murder, said he committed the act
because he lost job and was irritated, police said.
</P>
<P>
Zoda said he had become jobless about a week ago and around
that time decided he wanted to kill someone, according to police.
</P>
</TEXT>
