<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Reactivate Barter Trade With Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is to reactivate
barter trade with Myanmar as this approach has proven to benefit
both countries in the past, Transport Minister Ling Liong Sik
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, both members of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations, reached an agreement in this regard when he visited
Myanmar last month, Ling told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
During Ling's meeting with Myanmar trade and economic planning
ministers, the two sides agreed to reactivate barter trade which
ceased several years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries would sign a memorandum of
understanding soon to formalize their intention to reactivate the
bilateral barter trade.
</P>
<P>
Ling said the Myanmar government had previously regarded barter
trade as illegal trading but has now concurred with Malaysia's
stance that both countries stand to benefit much from such trading
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
Ling said that the now-defunct barter trade between Malaysia's
northern state of Pulau Pinang and Myanmar once stood at 800
million ringgit (over 210 million U.S. dollars) a year, which he
said "is a very attractive figure." 
</P>
</TEXT>
