<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Confidence of Consumers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A survey conducted recently by
MasterCard International showed that the Chinese consumers are
optimistic about the quality of life and China's economic
development while they are mainly worried about employment issue.
</P>
<P>
The survey, carried out in 13 Asia-Pacific countries and
regions including Australia, China, India, Japan and Republic of
Korea, asks the respondents to predict the future of five economic
factors which include: employment, the economy, regular income,
the stock market and quality of life.
</P>
<P>
The current survey asked consumers for their views on the
period from June to December 1999.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of the answers, the MasterIndex of consumer
confidence is calculated based upon ranges from 0 to 100, with 0
as the most pessimistic and 100 as most optimistic. The index
error was five percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey is held twice a year and was introduced in the
general Asia-Pacific region in 1993 and in China in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The latest index shows that most Asian people believe the
region is back on its feet and that they are optimistic about the
market.
</P>
<P>
The result of the China survey, carried out in Beijing,
Shanghai and Guangzhou, indicated that the index has increased to
63.6 from last time's 54.7. The current score is the highest of
the last three.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-based MasterCard International is a credit card
association consisting of 23,000 financial member organizations.
There are over 700 million MasterCard holders worldwide,
accounting for 35 percent of the world credit card market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
