<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Takes Bold Move to Revitalize State Sector (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Charles Tank, who rates China's banks at Moody's in New York,
said that the AMC scheme "should deliver substantial benefits to
the four banks in terms of enhanced asset quality and capital
levels, and enhanced profitability and liquidity."
</P>
<P>
As for the enterprises, those selected as qualified for debt-to-
equity swaps have to have viable market for their products,
advanced technology, and efficient management.
</P>
<P>
In applying for such conversions, they also have to submit
persuasive drafts elaborating on matching measures they would take
to improve performance such as reducing the workforce,
establishing a modern enterprise mechanism, and improving
management.
</P>
<P>
According to the AMC scheme, after the economic situation of
the enterprise has taken a turn for the better, the shares
controlled by the AMC will be returned to the enterprises, either
by listing the company, transfer or buy-back by the enterprise
concerned.
</P>
<P>
No single remedy exists for China's SOE reform, nor should debt-
to-equity swaps be taken as the final measure by all State
enterprises to evade repaying bank loans, according to Zhang
Chunlin, an expert on SOE reform.
</P>
<P>
The policy is intended to prioritize companies with high asset-
liability ratios, which have resulted from the lack of
recapitalization by the State in the past, and these companies
should have few fundamental weaknesses outside of a large
inherited debt burden, Zhang stressed.
</P>
<P>
Envisioning the nation's two-decade SOE reform, Zhang said, "
While those qualified enterprises will take advantage of the debt-
to-equity swaps and improve performance, about one-third or even
more State enterprises will have to be liquidated in the end and
stop wasting social resources."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Takes Bold Move to Revitalize State Sector (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- With an asset-liability ratio
of more than 117 percent, Beijing Cement Plant is virtually
bankrupt in economists' eyes.
</P>
<P>
But company managers have never been as optimistic about the
plant's prospects: they expect more than 20 million yuan in net
profit for next year after 70 percent of the plant's equity stake
is transferred to the loaner, the Xinda Asset Management Corp.
</P>
<P>
The plant is the first, followed by the Shanghai Coking Co. Ltd,
to benefit from a nationwide campaign to examine and clear bad
debts the State-owned sector has owed the major State banks.
Experts estimate these debts will involve about one trillion yuan
(about 120.9 billion U.S. dollars) of non-performing loans
belonging to about a half of the total SOEs.
</P>
<P>
To meet its goal, China has set up four asset management
companies (AMCs) -- Huarong, Xinda, Changcheng, Dongfang -- to
absorb the non-performing loans of its four big banks, the
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, China Construction Bank,
Agricultural Bank of China and Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
After taking over these banks' non-performing loans and
converting the bad debts into shares in the enterprises, the AMCs
will earn dividends and can take part in decision-making at the
firms.
</P>
<P>
"Swapping the debts of some qualified enterprises for equity
stake in the enterprises will rescue them from the edge of
bankruptcy and enable them to improve performance, instead of
liquidating all the deficit-ridden State enterprises
indiscriminately," said an official surnamed Duan from the State
Economic and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
Hailed as the boldest move ever adopted in reforming the debt-
ridden State-owned sector, the debt-to-equity swaps are expected
to create a win-win situation for both the loaners and the debtors,
economists said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
