<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Industry Grows Faster in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China's industry grew faster
in August than in July, with state-owned and foreign funded
sectors expanding more rapidly and the private sector slowing down.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the National Bureau of Statistics (NBC) show that
industrial output totaled 166.6 billion yuan in August, increasing
9.5 percent year-on-year. The growth rate was 0.2 percentage
points higher than in July.
</P>
<P>
Increasing government investment in fixed assets and
technological innovation helped boost the growth rate of output of
state-owned enterprises by 0.6 percentage points over July.
</P>
<P>
Foreign funded enterprises continued to lead the country's
industry in terms of output growth, increasing 13.7 percent year-
on-year and 0.8 percentage points more than in July.
</P>
<P>
However, lackluster investment activity in the private sector
pulled its growth rate down by 2.6 percentage points in August.
Industrial output of the private sector grew by 11 percent in
August, compared with 13.6 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
Exports of industrial products surged by 13.1 percent year-on-
year, 6.5 percentage points higher than the average growth rate of
the previous seven months.
</P>
<P>
Output of raw materials continued to grow in August. Sales of
industrial products also improved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massive Gas Field Found in Northern China Basin (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hu Wenrui, director of the Changqing Petroleum Exploration
Bureau (CPEB), a subsidiary of the China National Petroleum
Corporation (CNPC), said his firm confirmed a gas-bearing area of
2,500 square kilometers in the Ordos basin in early September,
precluding the verification of two gas zones with 100 billion
cubic meters of proven reserves each.
</P>
<P>
After 50 years of exploration, CPEB has located a total of 36
oil-gas fields in the Ordos basin, the country's second largest
sedimentary basin with an area of 370,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The Ordos basin sprawls across Shaanxi, Shanxi and Gansu
provinces and the Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia autonomous
regions. China's first oil well was sunk in Ordos in 1907.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, cumulative proven hydrocarbon reserves
there were reported to be 1.05 billion tons, of which 600 million
tons remain untapped.
</P>
<P>
Based on current exploration results, CPEB's geologists believe
that potential hydrocarbon reserves in the Ordos basin are around
12 billion tons, of which gas reserves are six to eight trillion
cubic meters, accounting for nearly 20 percent of the national
total.
</P>
<P>
Currently, CPEB has an annual crude production capacity of 4.3
million tons. The bureau also has an annual natural gas production
capacity of 2.2 billion cubic meters and three long-distance
pipelines transporting gas to Beijing, Xi'an and Yinchuan are now
operational. By 2003, targeted output for the region is expected
to generate 10 million tons of oil equivalent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Calls for Integrated Efforts to Raise Literacy Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif has called for integrated efforts to raise the
literacy rate as well as improve education standard in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In his message on the International Literacy Day Wednesday,
Sharif underlined the need to realize the fact that quick take-off
for development is not possible without achieving 80 percent
literacy rate in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"And to achieve this target we, as a nation, will have to take
extra-ordinary measures," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif asked the intellectuals, writers, journalists,
educationists and representatives of non-governmental
organizations (NGO) to come forward and contribute to this noble
cause so that inequalities of educational opportunities could be
removed altogether within a short span of time.
</P>
<P>
He said the Pakistani government has decided to take
revolutionary steps for achieving a target of 70 percent literacy
rate by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The National Education Policy is intended to raise primary
enrollment from 74.8 percent to 90 percent by the year 2002, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In order to provide quality primary education facilities to all
the school age children, 45,000 new primary schools will be
established in the country, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Literacy Commission (PMLC), he said, has
been assigned the task of formulating and implementing a
comprehensive non-formal primary education program under which
free education facilities will be provided to the deprived
segments of the society.
</P>
<P>
"The PMLC would set up 82,000 new community schools by the year
2003. This program is aimed at multiplying the government's
endeavors in providing primary education to millions of children,"
said Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that Pakistan is now spending 2.2 percent of its
GNP on education. "This is being gradually increased to four
percent by the year 2003." 
</P>
</TEXT>
