<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massive Gas Field Found in Northern China Basin (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Uranium ore deposits have also been discovered in the
northwestern area of the basin while a further six trillion tons
of potential sylvine deposits are estimated to be buried in the
central region of the basin.
</P>
<P>
Apart from these finds, geothermal energy resources have been
reported in the southern and western rims of the basin, all buried
at shallow strata and located in a densely-populated area which
will facilitate easy development and provide a promising potential
market.
</P>
<P>
However, the CPEB's most surprising and exciting discovery, and
the one which has attracted most attention from some quarters, is
of vast underground water resources in the central and northern
areas of the basin; a place where the local people have long been
combating drought.
</P>
<P>
A bureau survey indicates that there are water reserves of 11
trillion cubic meters at a depth of less than 600 meters covering
an area of 140,000 square kilometers. The freshwater resources are
reckoned to be close to seven trillion cubic meters. Once water
pipelines are constructed, all regions in the locality could see
an end to the threat of droughts, said sources from CPEB.
</P>
<P>
Other discoveries in the basin include gypsum, asbestos,
limestone, quartzite and bentonite.
</P>
<P>
The Ordos basin is a comparatively poverty-stricken area. And
the CPEB's discovery is expected to give a strong boost to the
local economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
