<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DVD Software Market to Expand in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 7 (Xinhua) -- A market analysis report
released Tuesday predicted that 11 percent of U.S. homes will own
at least one DVD device by the end of 1999, and 58 percent by 2002.
</P>
<P>
According to Strategy Analytics forecast, U.S. sales of DVD
software will reach 57 million discs this year, worth 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars, and by 2005 more than 1.3 billion discs will be
shipped annually, worth 36 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Annual sales of DVD devices will reach 9.1 million units in
1999 and will continue to soar, reaching 52 million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
TV-based DVD video players are becoming the format of choice
for movie fans and videophiles, the market research firm said. DVD
also will become a standard feature of home PC systems within the
next year or so.
</P>
<P>
DVD PCs currently account for 75 percent of the installed base,
the research firm said, but this share will fall to 59 percent by
2002 as TV-based DVD becomes more widespread.
</P>
<P>
Currently only 4 percent of U.S. households own DVD video
players. But Strategy Analytics predicted that the shift from
video home systems to DVD software will happen quite rapidly,
since early DVD owners are the avid movie and video enthusiasts
who account for a major share of pre-recorded video sales and
rentals.
</P>
<P>
"DVD is set to become the dominant packaged media platform for
the next decade," the firm said. "DVD players will be everywhere,
and discs will be even more pervasive than CDs are today."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
