<HEADLINE> APEC Senior Officials End Talks on Ministerial Meeting Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials
of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum ended their
talks here Wednesday on the agenda of the forthcoming ministerial
meeting preceding the 7th informal meeting of APEC leaders.
</P>
<P>
The participants in the meeting agreed to the outline of the
papers that will be presented to the APEC ministerial meeting
scheduled for Thursday and Friday, New Zealand's Maarten Wevers,
chairman of the senior officials meeting, told a press conference
after the conclusion of the talks.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the participants did not reach a final
agreement on all the issues discussed. According to the official,
the discussions over the past two days generally focused on three
major topics proposed by New Zealand -- to expand opportunities
for doing business throughout the region, to work with other
economies to strengthen the functioning of markets and to broaden
support for and understanding of APEC in its respective
communities.
</P>
<P>
"What we have been doing here over the last couple of days was
to put final touches on specific proposals and papers," he said.
Specifically, he said that the participants discussed individual
and collective action plans, APEC's contribution to the World
Trade Organization, the issues of electronic commerce, business on
the Internet, trade facilitation among a broad range of other
issues.
</P>
<P>
After the conclusion of the senior officials meeting, APEC
foreign and trade ministers will meet here over the next two days
to make preparations for the 7th informal meeting of APEC leaders
on September 12-13.
</P>
<P>
APEC was established in 1989 in response to the growing
interdependence among Asia-Pacific economies. It is a grouping of
21 regional economies set up to improve the stability, security
and prosperity of its peoples.
</P>
<P>
It now groups Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, China's
Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua
New Guinea, Peru, the Philippines, Russia, Singapore, South Korea,
Chinese Taipei, Thailand, the United States and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
