<HEADLINE> Greek Quake Death Toll Rises to 38 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from Tuesday
afternoon's powerful earthquake in the Greek capital of Athens has
risen to 38, including 14 children and infants.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake measuring 5.9 on the Richter scale occurred at 2:
56 p.m. local time Tuesday and was centered in the Mount Parnitha
region, some 20 kilometers north of Athens.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 persons were injured, 39 of them in a serious
condition, while 84 persons were missing or trapped in the rubble
of five factories and more than 50 collapsed buildings.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 aftershocks shook Athens until dawn Wednesday,
with the latest two both registering 4.2 on the Richter scale at 6:
20 a.m. and 6:35 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
About 1,500 firemen, 400 soldiers and 25 units from the special
damage prevention squad, accompanied by sniffer dogs, dug through
the rubble of the crumbled buildings and factories throughout the
night trying to extricate trapped persons.
</P>
<P>
Schools in Athens and the usually busy Athens Stock Exchange
will remain closed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A 19-member Turkish rescue team arrived in Athens early
Wednesday on a CN-235 military aircraft and joined Greek teams
digging through the rubble to search for survivors.
</P>
<P>
France and Russia have promised to send rescue teams to Athens
soon.
</P>
<P>
The last time Athens was shaken to such an extent was in
February 1981, when an earthquake measuring around 7.1 on the
Richter scale struck the Gulf of Corinth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
