<HEADLINE> China's Major Oilfield to Be Partly Listed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Zhongyuan Petroleum Company
Limited, a subsidiary of China's major oil producer, the Zhongyuan
Oil Exploration Bureau, will make its initial public offering (IPO)
of stock on September 10, Xinhua learned today.
</P>
<P>
The company, based in Puyang, Henan Province in central China,
will be offering 170 million A shares on the Shenzhen Stock
Exchanges at a price of 4.89 yuan per share.
</P>
<P>
The company was formed after a restructuring of the former
fourth oil collecting plant and the natural gas pool of the
Zhongyuan Oil Exploration Bureau, best known as the Zhongyuan
Oilfield.
</P>
<P>
According to information released by the company, by the end of
1998 it had total assets of one billion yuan and a net worth of
650 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The company produced 630,000 tons of crude oil and 700 million
cubic meters of natural gas in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Its revenue and net profit from major business in 1998 were 1.3
billion yuan and 160 million yuan, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Funds raised from the IPO will be spent on the development of a
new oil field, expansion of natural gas production capacity, gas
processing and other projects, the company said.
</P>
<P>
If the IPO proves successful, the company will have a total of
680 million shares, of which 75 percent will be held by the
Zhongyuan oilfield, and the remaining 25 percent by the public.
</P>
