<HEADLINE> Singapore Swimmer Keeps SEA Games Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A Singaporean swimmer who
failed a drug test was allowed by the South East Asian Games
executive Wednesday to keep her gold medal, according to officials
and reports.
</P>
<P>
An official at the Singapore National Olympic Council said the
decision over the 13-year-old Nicolette Teo was reached at the
meeting in Brunei.
</P>
<P>
According to television here, the committee had decided "it was
not deliberate but a case of ignorance."
</P>
<P>
Teo who is asthmatic, had tested positive for terbutaline, a
substance commonly found in medication for the illness.
</P>
<P>
Terbutaline is on the list of stimulants banned by the world
swimming body FINA although its use is permitted if an athlete
declares it before a drug test.
</P>
<P>
Teo set a new Under-14 national record for the 200 meters
breastroke at the games in Brunei last month. 
</P>
