<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Poll Gives President Obasanjo Pass Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A poll found that a majority of
the respondents in Nigeria thought President Olusegun Obasanjo had
performed above average in his first hundred days in office.
</P>
<P>
The poll conducted last week by The Post Express newspaper said
that among the 553 persons polled, 339 representing 61.30 percent
said that the president had done well in addressing the problems
confronting Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll results released by the paper Monday, 164
persons or 29.66 percent of the respondents, did not think the
president has done well while 50 persons or 9.04 percent were
indifferent.
</P>
<P>
Most of those who gave the president a pass mark praised his
handling of the fuel crisis which characterized the General Sani
Abacha era and continued till the handing over of the power by the
military to the new civilian administration in May this year.
</P>
<P>
They also commended Obasanjo administration's policies towards
better telephone services, employment generation and the
retirement of military officers.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, nearly all those who said that the president
had not done well criticized his tardiness in addressing the
electricity problem which has crippled many small and medium-scale
industries and made life painful for ordinary Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
They also slammed the president for not moving decisively
against armed robbers and other social miscreants who have made
the nation's major cities unsafe for law-abiding citizens.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the nationwide poll sought an assessment of
the performance of the president by Nigerians of all walks of
life, including men and women of diverse political persuasion and
ethnic background. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
