<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Cabinet Reshuffle Draws Mixed Reactions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The cabinet reshuffle designed
to streamline public service and enhance efficiency has drawn
different reactions, mainly along partisan lines.
</P>
<P>
Richard Leakey, Head of Civil Service, threw his weight behind
the reshuffle announced Monday by Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi, and urged Kenyans to fully support it.
</P>
<P>
Leakey described the reshuffle, with the number of the
ministries dwindling from 27 to 15 and one ministry having more
than one head, as "the best thing that has ever happened to Kenya
in recent times", according to Wednesday's East African Standard
daily.
</P>
<P>
The move will help reduce the government's pay package and cut
down on expenditure incurred annually in renting offices and
fueling cars for ministers, Leakey said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Opposition legislators, led by Mwai Kibaki, however, dismissed
the reshuffle as inconsequential to Kenya's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"It is an exercise in futility and a big disappointment to the
nation. It will lead to inefficiency and confusion," Kibaki said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Stock brokers said that the stock market was still waiting for
the government's full economic recovery blueprint before any
comments could be made.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Association of Manufacturers welcomed the changes as
evidence of Moi's seriousness to jump-start the stalled economy.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy has been on the decline since the International
Monetary Fund suspended its 205 million U.S. dollars loan in July
1997 in protest against corruption and poor governance in the east
African country.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth dropped from 4.6 percent in 1996 to 2.3
percent in 1997. In 1998 it stood at 1.8 percent and this year it
is expected to be less than 1.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
