<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Sliding, Dollar Surge in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices in Tokyo closed
lower for the second straight day Wednesday, as economic
indicators suggested that Japan's gross domestic product (GDP)
data for the April-June quarter may be worse than expected.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 66.12 points, or 0.37
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 17,641.38.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 2.05 points or 0.14 percent to 1,502.
57.
</P>
<P>
Stagnant capital investment by Japanese companies, announced by
the Finance Ministry on Tuesday, has stirred fears that the second-
quarter GDP will be lower than expected, a dealer said. Japan's
GDP data is scheduled to be released on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section remained sluggish, edging down to
484.58 million shares from 487.07 million shares Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi Electronic Corp. was the day's most heavily traded
issue.
</P>
<P>
Investors generally sit on the sidelines ahead of the GDP
announcement, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Share prices, however, will not fall sharply even if the GDP
figures are lower than expected, as weak GDP data will force the
government to take additional stimulus measures to boost the
economy, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outnumbered gainers by 831 to 363, with 144 issues remaining
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar rose against the
yen as dealers adjusted their short or oversold dollar positions
ahead of the release of Japan's GDP data.
</P>
<P>
At 5 p.m., the U.S. currency was quoted at 111.20-24 yen, up
from 110.77-80 yen at 9 a.m., and from 110.70-80 yen in late
overnight trading in New York. The dollar was traded at 110.79-82
yen in Tokyo late Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
