<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outlook Negative for Global Reinsurance Industry: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The global ratings agency
Standard &AMP; Poor's said Tuesday that outlook for the global
reinsurance industry remains negative.
</P>
<P>
This is because combined ratios are expected to rise as pricing
and low reserve levels compound to generate underwriting losses,
the agency said in a global industry report.
</P>
<P>
"While investment income on the very strong capital levels
bailed out most reinsurers last year, these returns are not
sustainable over the long term," added the report.
</P>
<P>
Reinsurance refers to insuring under a contract by which a
first insurer is relieved of part or all of the risk, which
devolves upon another insurer.
</P>
<P>
For the global reinsurance market, Standard &AMP; Poor's pointed
out two themes that have held constant throughout the 1990s --
globalization and flight to quality. "These themes will remain
dominant through the next decade as the second tier of reinsurers
struggle to achieve scale and broaden the range of products and
services provided," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report also discussed the emerging convergence of insurers
with banks and the capital markets, with reinsurers at a critical
nexus of this trend.
</P>
<P>
"Reinsurers are performing a number of roles from the provider
of risk to packaging and, perhaps most frequently, as purchasers
of insurance-linked bonds," the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, capital market alternatives are still too costly, too
cumbersome and too time-consuming to represent an immediate threat
to reinsurers. Nevertheless, the ratings agency warns that
disintermediation is a real threat to the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
