<HEADLINE> New China Grows Amid Stability (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After 50 years of development, especially the past 20 years,
China's total economic volume has climbed to the seventh in the
world, with comprehensive national strength obviously increased,
international status constantly raised and people's lives largely
improved.
</P>
<P>
An official with the World Bank said: "Other countries would
have to spend centuries to reach the achievements that China has
in one generation."
</P>
<P>
With 900 million rural residents, the stability of rural areas
is essential to the national good. In the early 1980s, China
introduced the household contract responsibility system with
remuneration linked to output in rural areas, which greatly
motivated farmers' enthusiasm in production and resulted in
unprecedented prosperity in China's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
To date, the average annual income of Chinese farmers has risen
from 44 yuan (about 5.5 U.S. dollars) 50 years ago to more than 2,
100 yuan (about 256 U.S. dollars) now, the issue of providing
adequate food and clothing to the 1.2 billion people has been
basically solved, and China is entering a stage of comfortable
life for its people.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has always paid attention to stability
through the whole process of reform and development, pilot
projects always preclude key national reforming measures. The
enduring needs of the masses and all social sectors are taken into
full consideration to ensure that all reforms proceed in a stable
social environment.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has also been strictly vigilant over
issues which have emerged in the process of reform and development
that may affect stability, and promptly adopted measures to solve
them.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, facing an "overheated" economy and inflation pressure,
the Chinese government adopted appropriately tight financial and
monetary policies to strictly control money supply, stabilize
financial situation and control the scale of infrastructure
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
