<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 06:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Hails King's Visit to Kuwait As Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian officials hailed King
Abdullah Bin Hussein's just concluded visit to Kuwait as a
successful landmark which would herald a new era in bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The visit marked a new beginning of Jordanian-Kuwaiti
relations, Prime Minister Abdul Raouf Rawabedh said in a
statement after Abdullah concluded his two-day official visit to
Kuwait on Tuesday, the first by a Jordanian ruler in nearly a
decade.
</P>
<P>
"The summer clouds between the two countries" had disappeared,
the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
In a departure cable to Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber Ahmad Sabah,
Abdullah said Jordan would stand by the emirate over the prisoner
issue, a sensitive issue between Iraq and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait claims that Iraq was holding some 600 Kuwaiti war
prisoners captured during the 1990 Gulf Crisis, triggered by
Iraq's invasion of the emirate. Iraq denies the charges.
</P>
<P>
Amman hoped King Abdullah's visit to Kuwait would restore
bilateral ties to levels prior to the Gulf Crisis, during which
Kuwait severed its ties with Jordan and accused Amman of siding
with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
After taking the throne in February this year, Abdullah is
apparently following a policy of keeping friendly relations with
all Arab countries, including its neighbor Iraq and Iraq's arch
Arab foes Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The monarch said on many occasions that his kingdom would not
improve ties with one country at the expense of another.
</P>
<P>
Currently Jordan depends on Iraq as its only source of crude
oil, importing some 75,000 barrels a day from Baghdad under the
United Nations' oil-for-food program for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordan also hoped to reopen the labor markets in
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia as labor export was one of the pillar
industries of the debt-ridden desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian workers in Kuwait had remitted billions of dollars
back home each year before they were expelled from the emirate
during the Gulf Crisis.
</P>
<P>
Less than 30,000 Jordanians are currently working in Kuwait as
against 350,000 before the Gulf Crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
