<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Lowers Fuel Prices Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has lowered gasoline
prices by 200 Lebanese pounds (about 0.13 U.S. dollars) per 20
liters, the second drop after two prices hikes in August, the
Daily Star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a decrease in world oil prices, Lebanese Oil Minister
Suleiman Traboulsi decreed that a 20-liter tank of 92 octane
gasoline would cost 12,500 pounds (about 8.33 dollars), unleaded
gasoline would be priced at 12,800 pounds (about 8.53 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The decree also lowered the price per 20 liters of 98
octane gasoline to 12,900 pounds (about 8.6 dollars), increased
the cost of kerosene from 6,600 pounds (about 4.4 dollars)
to 6,800 pounds (about 4.53 dollars), and kept the cost of
diesel fuel at 6,100 pounds (about 4.06 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The decrease followed a 200 pounds cut last week. The
minister has said that prices will be modified on a weekly
basis according to fluctuations in international oil prices.
</P>
<P>
In August, prices first rose 400 pounds (about 0.26
dollars) and then 300 pounds (about 0.2 dollars). In April,
the Cabinet imposed a 2,000 pounds (about 1.33 dollars) surtax
on every 20 liters to bolster the government's coffers.
</P>
<P>
Traboulsi said the hikes were necessary to offset increases
in international prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
