<HEADLINE> World Bank Expected to Approve $140M Credit to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) board is
expected to approve a 140 million U.S. dollars structural
adjustment credit to Zimbabwe, an official of the bank has said.
</P>
<P>
World Bank resident representative to Zimbabwe Thomas Allen
said Tuesday that he was optimistic next Thursday's meeting would
agree to release the funds from the bank's International
Development Association.
</P>
<P>
The money to support a program to get Zimbabwe's economy back
on track would be followed by a further two follow-up structural
adjustment credits if the program remained on track, the Herald
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank's intention to provide structural adjustment credit
comes in the wake of last month's approval of a 194-million-dollar
standby facility by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Allen said recent developments in the country's land
resettlement were encouraging.
</P>
<P>
Workable land reform could contribute significantly to poverty
reduction, he said. But the World Bank official expressed
disappointment at the rate at which the land reform was taking
place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
