<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Get Import Trade Financing Facility with IDB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Industry Bank
Wednesday signed here with the Islamic Development Bank (IDB) the
Import Trade Financing (ITF) Facility agreement, amounting to 10
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The facility, which is offered on short term basis, is to
assist Malaysian importers in the purchase of materials such as
industrial raw materials, intermediate goods and capital goods
from member countries as well as non-member countries of the
Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
Bank Industry Malaysia Executive Director Mohamed Saleh Ghazali
told reporters that there were already few companies which could
be provided with this facility and he was confident that the total
amount, which was approved on June 19, 1999, will be fully
disbursed by next year.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth line of ITF facility. The bank received the
first line of ITF amounting to 10 million dollars in 1988, while
the second and third line agreements, amounting to 10 million
dollars each were signed in December 1991 and February 1997
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The three lines had since been fully utilized and in total, 26
companies had benefited from the previous ITF facilities," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Bank Industry was appointed by the Ministry of Finance to act
as one of the executing agents as well as a guarantor for
Malaysian companies utilizing this IDB facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
