<HEADLINE> Malaria Kills 14,000 In Southern Africa Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- About 14,000 people die of
malaria in southern Africa every year, with half of them being
children below the age of 14, the World Health Organization (WHO)
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
WHO program officer Graham Root Tuesday told participants at a
four-day seminar held in Harare on School Health and HIV/AIDS and
Sexually Transmitted Diseases Prevention in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Despite efforts by regional governments to wipe out the menace,
malaria has remained one of the greatest killers in Africa.
Children have been the hardest-hit, especially in countries
ravaged by war, the representatives said.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the objective of controlling malaria, the WHO is
trying to lobby governments in the region to include malaria
education in their curricula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
