<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Few U.S. Companies to Cut IT Investment in 2000: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 7 (Xinhua) -- Only 7 percent of
companies in the United States and Canada indicated that they will
cut information technology (IT) spending after Y2K projects have
been completed, according to a survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
International Data Corporation (IDC), a U.S. market research
firm, conducted the recent survey among 1,145 North American
companies on Y2K effect.
</P>
<P>
"The time lines that companies have chosen to address Y2K
compliance are having an immediate impact on short-term IT
investments," IDC said. "However, the long-term prospects for the
continued proliferation of IT remain strong."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, according to the IDC, Y2K projects will have
a "dampening effect," hampering spending on other IT projects, and
this effect will only worsen as the year 2000 draws closer.
</P>
<P>
"There is a very definite correspondence between achieving
compliance late in 1999 and the need to postpone non-Y2K projects
or reduce non-Y2K spending," IDC said.
</P>
<P>
Y2K projects will have the greatest negative impact on spending
for software applications, end-user and server hardware, and
network upgrades.
</P>
<P>
But as the survey results indicated, despite Y2K projects,
companies are still willing to invest in technology that can give
them a differential, competitive advantage, such as Internet
applications as well as products with lower price point or
critical to ongoing maintenance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
