<HEADLINE> Turkey Sends Search and Rescue Team to Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkey sent a 20-man search
and rescue team early Wednesday morning to save survivors in the
ruins of the collapsed buildings after the 5.9-magnitude
earthquake hit Athens, capital of Greece, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Ministry Crisis Administration Center said in a
statement Wednesday that Turkey's Search and Rescue Association
had sent the team to release the survivors trapped in the
collapsed buildings in Athens with the coordination of the General
Staff of the Turkish Armed Forces, Interior Ministry and Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 people were killed, dozens injured and many more
trapped in an estimated 30 collapsed buildings in the Greek
capital of Athens when a powerful quake struck the city around 03:00
p.m. local time Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit sent a message
to his Greek counterpart Kostas Simitis to express Turkey's great
concern over the strong quake.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said in the message that Turkey is ready to provide all
kinds of help to Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece have improved strained ties between the two
countries since the Greek government immediately decided to send a
search and rescue team and to provide material aid to Turkey,
which was hit by the 7.4-magnitude earthquake on August 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
