<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang, Howard Hold Talks in Canberra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China is satisfied with its
present relations with Australia, visiting Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said here Wednesday in talks with Australian Prime Minister
John Howard.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the two nations have maintained frequent contact and
exchanges of visits, Jiang said, adding that both sides have good
relations regarding some major international and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
He said that bilateral consultation and dialogue is continuing
to be strengthened and bilateral trade and economic relations are
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing visit is intended to further develop the friendship
between the two peoples, expand mutually beneficial cooperation
and push forward bilateral relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1972 when the two countries set up diplomatic ties, Jiang
said, bilateral relations have been progressing smoothly. The Sino-
Australian ties have maintained good momentum through the
concerted efforts of both sides, especially in recent years, the
Chinese president said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, which proceeded in a "friendly manner,"
Jiang and Howard reviewed the development of bilateral ties since
the two nations forged diplomatic.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders said that China and Australia, both as Asian-
Pacific nations with important influence, share wide-ranging
common interests in safeguarding world and regional security and
stability, as well as promoting regional economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to make greater efforts in exploring new areas of
cooperation and to work together for the long-term, stable and
sound Sino-Australian relationship geared to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Howard said that Jiang's current visit is very important for
Australia, which indicates that bilateral relations are mature and
continue to be promoted.
</P>
<P>
He is convinced that the visit will further strengthen the
existing friendly cooperation between the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Australia-China ties as one of its most
important external relationships, Howard said Australia values its
long-term cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
Australia is satisfied with the current bilateral relations, he
said, though there still exist some different viewpoints, this
cannot become an obstacle preventing the two nations from
furthering cooperation on the basis of seeking common ground and
mutual benefit while preserving differences.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two leaders agreed, based on
strengthening the present dialogue and consultations, to set up a
regular meeting mechanism -- an annual meeting between leaders of
the two nations and between the two foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The time and form of the meeting will be arranged in accordance
with the need, they said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed to continue to strengthen consultations
and cooperation in multilateral international organizations and on
some major international and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are willing to make concerted efforts for a fair and
reasonable international economic and financial order, they
claimed.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to strengthen bilateral cooperation in the
consular services, mining industry and enforcement of law.
</P>
<P>
They said that they are pleased and satisfied with the
consensus the two sides reached on a framework joint statement on
network economy and e-business cooperation.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, the two attended a signing ceremony for five
documents between the two nations: a memorandum of understanding
on trade and investment cooperation in mining industry and energy
resources; a memorandum of understanding on cooperation in the
mining industry; a consular agreement; an agreement on Australia's
continuous implementation of consular duties in the future Macao
Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China;
and a memorandum of understanding on anti-crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
