<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Firms Post 477M Dollar Debt Suspensions in Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The total liabilities involving
the suspension of debt repayments among Philippine corporations
reached 19.071 billion pesos (477 million U.S. dollars) during the
first semester of 1999, an official report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A report of the country's Securities and Exchange Commission
(SEC) said that 10 cases were filed with the SEC from February to
July 1999, involving 16 corporations with total assets of 41.224
billion pesos (1 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report revealed that the total debt suspensions from 1982
to July 1999 reached 103 cases involving 133 corporations with
total assets of 177.192 billion pesos (4.4 billion dollars),
representing total liabilities of 139.4 billion pesos (3.5 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the period indicated, the year 1998 showed the biggest total
liabilities amounting to 96.34 billion pesos (2.4 billion
dollars), representing 46 corporations which filed debt suspension
applications with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 came second with 32 applications whose total
liabilities amounted to 12.8 billion pesos (32 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
In a related development, SEC Executive Director Eugene Reyes
said that the licensing of the securities market declined further
in 1998, compared to the previous year's 38.4 percent decline in
the number of registrants.
</P>
<P>
He said this was so because corporations tended to be skeptical
in conducting initial public offerings during the period due to
the lingering effects of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
If they do, only few interested people will buy the shares that
they are offering to the public because of the crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Eventually, this also resulted in the shrinking of income
supposed to be generated by the SEC from securities fees paid by
corporations, Reyes explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0243 </DOCNO>
