<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Mogao Grottoes Getting More High-Tech Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Mogao Grottoes just
outside the city of Dunghuang in northwest China's Gansu Province
are now being protected from the ravages of shifting sands by
Chinese scientists using newer high-tech methods.
</P>
<P>
The grottoes hold 45,000 square meters of murals and 2,000
figurines that were made from the fourth to the 14th centuries.
They were added to the UNESCO's world cultural heritage list and
began attracting thousands of visitors from around the world. But,
the unique cultural relics have long been threatened by sandstorms.
</P>
<P>
Every year some three to four thousand cubic meters of sand
are blown around them, so scientists have built three barriers
using plants and nylon. As a result, the sands around the grotto
area have been reduced by some 70 percent from a few years ago. As
more visitors come to this museum on the Gobi, Chinese scientists,
working with foreign colleagues, have done more researches on ways
to protect the relics.
</P>
<P>
They have built a monitoring station and a computer data bank
to record temperature, sunlight, and wind changes both inside and
outside the grottoes and have had scored some success in
preserving and recreating the murals through the use of computers.
People can now have a look at the murals without coming to
Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
Lasers and other high-tech methods are also being used to
clean and restore images on the murals and to understand the
coloration and pigmentation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990908.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500, September 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- World Bank President James D. Wolfensohn Tuesday
told Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit that the bank is
intensifying its commitment to assist the government in its
reconstruction and recovery programs in the aftermath of the
August 17 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
"I am very pleased to convey that the World Bank is preparing a
1 billion dollar package for Turkey to help finance the costs of
reconstruction and recovery," Wolfensohn said. "This package will
take the form of 300 million dollars in re-allocations from
existing loans to Turkey and up to 750 million dollars in new long-
term loans, which would be committed over the next three months."
(WB-Turkey)
</P>
<P>
