<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Patients Nearly 100,000 in Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of HIV/AIDS patients
in the countries of the Southeast Asian region has already reached
92,427, press reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 5.6 million people are feared to be carrying HIV
virus across the world, and the reported AIDS cases in Thailand,
Myanmar and India are very high, said World Health Organization
(WHO) officials Tuesday, who are here to attend the 52nd session
of the WHO Regional Committee for Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Officials and academics from Bangladesh, Bhutan, the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea, India, Indonesia, the Maldives,
Myanmar, Nepal, Sri Lanka and Thailand, and representatives of
different U.N. and international agencies and non-governmental
organizations were attending the week-long session, which started
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Some 83,357 AIDS cases were reported from Thailand, 6,252 from
India, and 2,312 patients were detected in Myanmar till March 1
this year," they said.
</P>
<P>
They expressed concern over the continued proliferation of
HIV/AIDS in the region except in Thailand where HIV had begun to
decline in different population groups.
</P>
<P>
Delegates stressed the need for concerted efforts to combat and
contain this menace as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
The WHO is providing support to the countries pursuing
prevention and control measures in the field of prevention of
sexually-transmitted infection, screening of blood, care for
people living with infection, and in epidemiological surveillance.
</P>
<P>
Delegates at the session earmarked different diseases including
tuberculosis, malaria, neo-natal tetanus and non-communicable
disease like cardiovascular as the major health threat in the
region, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
