<HEADLINE> Repair Work On 3,000-Year Old Chinese Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- China began repair work
recently on a 3,000-year-old tomb in Xishan, a city in east China'
s Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The project, which covers 18 buildings on 4 hectares of land,
is expected to cost 15 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
According to historical documents, the tomb was made for Tai Bo,
a prince of the Zhou Kingdom during the Shang Dynasty (16th-11th c.
B.C.), who established a school here and played an active role in
promoting social and economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
Tai Bo died 3,193 years ago and was buried on Hongnan Hill in
what is today the suburbs of the city. He is said to have 5
million descendants, who live in various parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the city has spent 50 million yuan on two
temples, a Tai Bo park, and a research institute to study his
cultural contributions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
