<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Takes New Measures to Control Foreign Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has
taken new measures to control foreign currency by setting up the
Foreign Currency Reserve Fund and the Foreign Exchange and Gold
Price Stabilization Fund.
</P>
<P>
The two new funds will be established under a decree signed by
Vietnam's Prime Minister Phan Van Khai last week, according to a
report of Vietnam's English daily Vietnam News on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two funds will be used as levers to ensure the soundness of
both Vietnam's foreign exchange reserves and its international
payment system.
</P>
<P>
The measures were designed to overcome shortcomings in the
country's foreign currency control system, said an official of
Vietnam State Bank.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam State Bank is prepared to intervene in the domestic
foreign exchange and gold markets if they fluctuate sharply.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Currency Reserve Fund will be used to invest in
different dealings in international monetary markets. They include
depositing money with overseas banks, buying and selling foreign
currencies and gold, and buying and selling stock shares in
foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Exchange and Gold Price Stabilization Fund will be
used to intervene in the domestic foreign currency and gold
markets in cases of great turbulence.
</P>
<P>
Forms of intervention include spot sales, term-sales, swaps and
other dealings.
</P>
<P>
The news decree becomes effective on September 14 and replaces
an existing foreign currency regulation fund established in April
1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
