<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Approves Bill to Toughen Penalties in Medicine Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has approved
in principle the Public Health Ministry's draft medicines bill
which imposes heavier penalties on unauthorized producers,
dispensers and importers, Bangkok Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The draft bill, approved Tuesday, will be forwarded to the
Council of State before going to the House of Representatives, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The draft also provides criteria for obtaining a permit to
advertise medical products, and empowers the Food and Drugs
Administration (FDA) to order advertisers to correct misleading
information.
</P>
<P>
The bill allows the FDA to ban production, sale and import of
medical products deemed unsafe for consumers.
</P>
<P>
Producers must bear responsibility for any damage caused by
their medical products, which are to be divided into three
categories: those requiring a physician's prescription, those that
must be dispensed by pharmacists, and over-the-counter drugs.
</P>
<P>
Medicines in the first and second categories must be clearly
separated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
