<HEADLINE> ADB Assists China in Urbanization Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the Asian
Development Bank (ADB), the Ministry of Construction and cities
across China gathered in Beijing on Tuesday to discuss the
challenges facing China's urbanization process, today's China
Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
A package of measures aiding urban infrastructure construction
is expected to emerge on Thursday, according to ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
Topics up for discussion by participants to the Urban Policy
Workshop include water supply, environmental management, urban
transport and infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Officials and consultants from the ADB will hold individual
meetings with the cities' representatives tomorrow to discuss
concrete financial assistance, the newspaper says.
</P>
<P>
The ADB has provided loans of 1.35 billion U.S. dollars to
China, together with offers of advanced technology valued at 29
million U.S. dollars. These have been conducive to the improvement
of China's urban living standards, said vice-minister of
Construction Zhao Baojiang.
</P>
<P>
The growth of China's urban economy and population has raised
demands for more urban public utilities, while the development of
urban infrastructure such as water supply, housing, roads and
bridges has generally been lagged behind, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate infrastructure facilities are mainly the result of
insufficient investment in urban infrastructure and shortage of
funds for urban infrastructure investment.
</P>
<P>
State financial sources have been very limited due to the
decentralization of infrastructure financing responsibilities to
local governments, which have limited funds from taxation, the
paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
