<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Guerrouj's World Record Highlights Golden League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, September 7 (Xinhua) -- World 1,500 chapion Hicham El
Guerrouj of Morocco stole the limelight from the jackpot hunters
when he added the 2,000 meters mark to his collection of world
records in the last leg of the IAAF Golden League here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Gerrouj, already the fastest man over 1,500 meters and one mile,
is the only athlete who now holds three world records. He clocked
four minutes 44.79 seconds to beat the old mark by the vast margin
of more than three seconds.
</P>
<P>
The previous mark of 4:47.88 was set by Algerian Noureddine
Morceli in July 1995 in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Wilson Kipketer of Denmark and Gabriela Szabo of Romania had
earlier completed their seventh Golden League victories to share a
one million jackpot.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer and Szabo outclassed the opposition again in the men's
800 meters and women's 5,000 meters respectively, pocketing 500,
000 U.S. dollars each for becoming the only two athletes to have
won all seven events in the series.
</P>
<P>
After letting Kenyans Robert Kibet and William Tanui set the
early pace, El Guerrouj kicked and raced the last 600 meters well
ahead of the rest of the field.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Paul Bitok was a distant second in 4:54.36 and Portugal'
s Rui Silva third in 4:54.66.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan steeplechaser Bernard Barmasai failed to complete a
clean sweep when he was beaten into second place by unfancied
Algerian Ali Ezzine.
</P>
<P>
World 3,000 meters steeplechase record holder Barmasai, who had
won all six previous races, was disqualified from the one million
jackpot after he said he had asked compatriot Christopher Koskei
to let him win in Zurich last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
