<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said in Melbourne, Australia,
yesterday that China and Australia must focus on new trade areas,
investment, science and technology and financial cooperation to
strengthen ties.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said in a speech at the Australia-China Trade and
Investment Summit that Sino-Australian economic cooperation and
trade have expanded from bilateral to regional and multilateral
fields.
</P>
<P>
-- The Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
Central Committee has decided to hold the 4th plenum of the 15th
CPC Central Committee between September 19 and 22 in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The session will focus on implementing the strategic plans
drawn up by the 15th National Congress of the CPC and on adopting
decisions on a number of major issues concerning the restructuring
and development of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
-- The Chinese government and people support the blindness
prevention and treatment project carried out in China by the Lion
Clubs International (LCI), one of world's leading charitable
organizations, Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao said yesterday at
a meeting with a LCI delegation headed by its president James
Ervin.
</P>
<P>
Hu praised the "Sightfirst China Action", a blindness
prevention and treatment project developed with the combined
efforts of China and the Lions Club International, as a
significant event.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin arrived at Canberra yesterday
afternoon. Australian Governor General William Deane hosted a
welcome banquet in honor of Jiang yesterday evening.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told Deane that positive momentum prevails in Sino-
Australian relations, with a frequent exchange of high-level
visits. And he hopes his trailblazing state visit boosts
friendship between the two countries and deepen bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao met with visiting Kuwaiti
Deputy Prime Minister and Defense Minister Sheik Salem Sabah Al-
Salem Al-Sabah and his party at the Great Hall of the People
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Hu said friendship between China and Kuwait can be traced back
to ancient times, and bilateral ties have witnessed considerable
growth since the establishment of diplomatic relations in 1971.
</P>
<P>
He thanked Kuwait for its support of China on issues concerning
Taiwan and human rights. The Chinese government and people cherish
the traditional friendship between the two countries and are
willing to push forward bilateral ties to a higher level through
joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China yesterday expressed strong indignation at the recent
landing by Japanese rightists on Diaoyu Island in the East China
Sea, saying it constituted a "serious encroachment on Chinese
territorial sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, three members of Seinensha, a Japanese right-wing
group, landed on the Chinese territory of Diaoyu Island, Foreign
Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi told a regular news briefing yesterday
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry yesterday made "solemn representations" to
the Japanese Government, and expressed its strong condemnation, he
said.
</P>
<P>
-- With the increasing use of the Internet worldwide,
prosecutors from different legal systems should join hands in
combating transnational crimes like fraud and corruption.
</P>
<P>
Eamonn M. Barnes, president of International Association of
Prosecutors (IAP), said the expansion of international cooperation
among prosecutors in cracking down on fraud and corruption is
particularly crucial in such an information-based society.
</P>
</TEXT>
