<HEADLINE> APEC Senior Officials Continue Talks on Ministerial Meeting Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AUCKLAND, New Zealand, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Senior officials
of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum are
continuing their talks here Wednesday on the agenda of the
forthcoming ministerial meeting preceding the 7th informal meeting
of APEC leaders.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day talks that started on Tuesday, the APEC
senior officials are set to propose topics of discussions for
their ministers, who will meet here on Thursday and Friday making
preparations for the 7th informal meeting of APEC leaders on
September 12-13.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that senior officials participating in the talks
will recommend that China and Chinese Taipei join the World Trade
Organization (WTO) before the start of the next round of global
trade talks in Seattle in November.
</P>
<P>
According to a draft report discussed in the talks Tuesday,
"Senior officials recommend to ministers that they... note the
progress that has been achieved in the negotiations on the
accession to the WTO of China and Chinese Taipei, and call for the
conclusion of these negotiations at the earliest opportunity, if
possible before the third WTO ministerial meeting in Seattle."
</P>
<P>
Necessary revisions will be made to the draft report before it
is submitted to trade ministers from the 21 APEC members.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between China and the United States on China's
entry into the WTO were suspended after the May 7 U.S. bombing of
the Chinese embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his U.S. counterpart Bill
Clinton are expected to meet on the sidelines of the APEC leaders
meeting on a series of major issues.
</P>
<P>
Besides talks on the WTO, the APEC leaders will discuss a broad
range of other major issues, such as the expansion of
opportunities for doing business throughout the APEC region, the
working with other economies to strengthen the functioning of
markets and the broadening of support for and understanding of
APEC in its respective communities.
</P>
<P>
They are also likely to discuss the crisis of East Timor. New
Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley has invited non-APEC
countries to participate in a "Special Ministers Meeting" on the
crisis to be held on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Those from non-APEC members to participate in this meeting will
include British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who is to arrive
here later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
APEC, which was created in 1989, now groups Australia, Brunei,
Canada, Chile, China, China's Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan,
Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, Peru, the
Philippines, Russia, Singapore, South Korea, Chinese Taipei,
Thailand, the United States and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
