<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rate Cuts Boost Business Confidence in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 7 (Xinhua) -- More relaxed financial
environments following the rapid decline in interest rates have
helped boost South Africa's business confidence, the South African
Chamber of Business (Sacob) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The business confidence index (BCI) rose marginally by 2.1
points in August to reach 92.2 points, Sacob said, predicting that
another percentage point could be trimmed by the end of December.
</P>
<P>
"In August, nine of the 13 indices used in determining
confidence levels were either neutral or positive. Seventy-one
percent of the respondents to Sacob's monthly manufacturing survey
nevertheless expect sales to improve over the next 12 months, the
highest level of expectation since April 1997," Sacob said.
</P>
<P>
It said that "as the more positive financial environment will
take time to filter through to the demand and supply side of the
economy, an improvement in real economic activity can be expected
in the remaining months of this year."
</P>
<P>
Sacob noted that further enhancement of the business mood would
most probably depend on positive developments in the real economy.
</P>
<P>
"Interest rates are not likely to decline as rapidly as was the
case during the first half of this year. A further reduction of
one percentage (point) is expected for this year, followed by
another one percent in the first half of next year," it said.
</P>
<P>
Sacob said that the prime lending rate now stands at 16.5
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
